            <Title>A promising planet</Title>
            <Text>A promising planet
Traveller’s Perch,
September 8, 2048
Far Flier was in a hurry to meet with the new class of cadets, but it would have to wait. He could feel Diver’s anxiety deepening, and he would have to go see her first. She was too deep into her link with Earth to fully convey her thoughts remotely, so he would just go to the Guardian headquarters and see what was up.
No wonder she had been unable to fully communicate with him. She was sitting motionless in the inner ring around the pulsing energy of the wormhole interface that was the heart of the Guardian’s galactic network, fully entangled with the humans she monitored. Most ambassadors connected to the interface from their homes or work sites, allowing them to attenuate the signal as needed. Always so conscientious, he thought with fondness.
The ozonish glow of the interface field highlighted the purple in her feathers. The sharpness of her beak, the way her arms looked poised for flight even when she was still, everything about her expressed the alertness that had drawn him to her. Fifty thousand years ago we would have soared together over the canyons of Traveller’s Perch, hunting for food, he thought, with not a little bit of desire to soar and swoop with her. Something gained, something given. At least we will have centuries to get to know each other.  He touched her mind lightly, politely, so as not to startle her.
“Aren’t you the diligent one,” he let her know. “Coming right to the source.”
“I didn’t really have a choice” she said, speaking out loud. “Earth is not exactly the strongest signal in the galaxy and I have to find Raefe’s mind. Something is happening and the wormhole interface is the best place to find it.”
“So what’s going on?” he asked.
“Well, there’s been an extreme storm on Earth that broke many of the walls they had erected to hold the rising seas back.  Raefe’s city was struck by a giant wave of ocean water. He was nearly killed, tens of thousands were. He and millions are homeless now.”
“That’s terrible! Is he injured?”
“No, but I don’t know how he’s taking it. And there’s more: I feel a surge from him — I think maybe the stress has strengthened his empathetic capabilities. Or possibly the opposite -- he’s always been a bit fragile, and the surge may have been a breakdown.”
“Well, I came at the right time. I wanted to get an update from you on Earth ahead of the Council meeting.”
“OK,” she said. “But just for a few minutes. I need to monitor things closely. And I’m just not sure everything coming from Earth makes it out of the interface into the waveform.”
He smiled at her dedication as a rookie ambassador. With time and experience she would become more relaxed and less reactive. As Guardians, they were more concerned about the sweep of history, less about the daily travails of the individuals and species they monitored.
“I’m sure Earth’s future will not be decided in the next few minutes,” he said. “You have a trainee, don’t you? Adno, as I recall. Ask her to monitor while we talk.”
She let him follow her thoughts to Adno, who seemed pleased to take on the task, but worried she was not up to it. Diver reassured her and they left the interface chamber for the tunnels that took them to cliff face outside of headquarters.
“It’s a full sky today,” he observed.
He felt the warm breeze that Prime’s light brought to them. High in the sky, Prime’s trinary mates, the Twins, shone like orange eyes against the red sky. Prime’s other two planets, Red Nest and Water Eye, shone like small yellow jewels on a head dress. The dance of these stars and planets drove the thermal cycle that all life on the planet lived by.
He felt contentment from Diver. He knew few people who derived as much satisfaction from raw nature as her, and it was one of the things that drew him to her.
 “Perhaps all this beauty will help to clarify our way forward,” he said. “Analysis Section thought that Earth showed a small yet definite promise that it may progress to Balance, where it would likely flourish. Should I be telling them that they may have been wrong?”
“No, in the long run they will be proven right,” she said. “But humans are still stuck in Optimization. Every problem they have, they try to invent a technology to solve. You can bet they’ll be discussing bigger sea walls now. Sometimes I wish I could yell through the interface ‘Look inside yourselves, the answer’s there.’ But on the plus side,  they belong to an order of animals that is predominantly social, able to accommodate a wide range of social structures, from small bands of less than 10 to herds of thousand. So they have that in their favor.”
“How does their genetics express itself in their ability to entangle?”
“Weakly, it would seem, although it’s hard to tell,” she answered. “I suspect that in the past they developed a very basic ability — they were able to colonize their entire world largely without the benefit of a common language, spoken or written. But for about 5,000 years, they have relied heavily on written language to organize elites in their society, and only in the last 200 years has written language become widespread outside the elites, and even then, not everywhere. And they have thousands of languages, although a handful are widespread. So as they’ve advanced technically, they’ve also had tugs pulling them apart, pushing them backwards in their social integration.”
“As happened with our ancestors,” he pointed out.
“Yes, I tell myself that, too,” she said. “But I think their Emergent phase was more extreme than ours. History is your passion -- what can you tell me about our beliefs in spirits during our Emergent and Optimization periods? The databases are hard to decode on that subject.”
“Well, I don’t think we need to figure that out just yet – I just need to give a preliminary report of your current findings. But for what it’s worth, twenty or thirty thousand years ago we believed that every kind of life was patterned after an invisible spirit that lived on Prime and flew here to lay eggs that became us or other kinds of life.”
“So how did people react when they learned Prime was a hot ball of gas and that there was a vacuum you couldn’t fly through between Prime and our planet? Or that Water Eye was inhabited by intelligent marine animals?”
He paused, letting his enhancements probe tens of thousands of years into databases of ancient histories. “Oh, right. At first there was some upset about it, but that discovery really launched us into a deeper understanding of physics. Ultimately that led to us discovering entanglement.”
“Hmm, Earth people went to their own moon and it didn’t have that effect, not totally. Wait a second --” 
He felt her mind slip away as Adno made contact with her. He could feel that she was mostly relieved by whatever news her trainee had for her.
“Sorry,” she said. “Adno wanted to let me know that he’s OK. He and his mate, Lina, have found a camp where they can eat and sleep for the time being. She confirms that his ability to entangle has become stronger. Adno suspects that as the shock of the flood wears off, he will also be less troubled by his abilities. We agree that he’s starting to come to grips with his empathic abilities for the first time. If we could just nudge that along…”
He looked at over the canyons, listening to whistle of the winds that traversed Traveller’s Perch. He felt Diver’s blend of hope and frustration but he wasn’t sure he had any advice. Perhaps he had been wrong to give her this species as her first assignment — if she failed because they were intractable, he knew she would take it personally. And maybe even blame him for giving her the assignment.
“Well, we are bound not to intervene too much. Soon, though, you may be able to contact him directly. In the meanwhile, you sit by the interface, what, hoping for a miracle?” he asked, hoping she understood that he was impressed by her effort. “As our friends on Water Eye say, ‘You can try to swim on land, but it won’t get any wetter.”
“Well, Earth’s not all that dry,” she joked. She sped through a litany of all the things she considered positives for humans. You have to love her enthusiasm, he thought. Or was it just that she was 400 years old and he was 1,200?
 “So what’s the crux of the issue here? What do I tell the Council is the indicator that we’re watching for movement?” he asked.
 “They have to make that breakthrough,” she said. “That moment when they learn to use their rationality to understand their irrationality. Their art is full of that, but they think of it as imaginary, not real. They’re like most other intelligent species, a blend of emotion and logic. But they think of those facets as opposites instead of complementary. That’s exactly what they need to shed, and begin to use their rationality to understand how to account for their irrationality.”
“Well, you seem to believe they can. Let’s just hope that humans do, too,” he said. “I knew you were the right person for this job. Most Guardians would have recommend abandoning this species to their own devices.”
“I can’t accept that they’re that hopeless,” she said, “Their abilities are buried — not nonexistent. If I sit in front of that interface I can sense the pure signal of a few thousand minds in that glow, unmediated by the interface network. It’s just extremely weak. But something very real is happening, even as we sit here. Hopefully, Raefe is not the only one being pushed forward by crisis. But I fear for them — their civilization is trapped in the classic spiral of decline. Those with the power to change things delude themselves and use their power to protect their own narrow interests. He’s just one person on a failing world.”
“Our work is hard,” Far Flier sighed. “We have failed with many species, and they’ve perished. Even when we succeed with a species, we always have to consider that at some later date they may revert and become a serious threat outside their own star systems.  But I sense that what troubles you most is the fate of this Raefe.”
“He has a hard life. He experiences his own gift as an affliction, and he sees himself as weak and useless.  
“Still, it’s a start for him and for you. Keep me informed. Next week is the Guardian Council meeting. At the very least, let’s talk about it there. Now I have to go.”
He hopped on the moving sidewalk that ran along the back of the cliff face and jumped off minutes later at the front entrance to Guardian headquarters. A’Nontans who weren’t involved with the Guardians sometimes congregated there — watching offworlders was a hobby for some of Traveller’s Perch’s natives. On all the Guardian worlds people enjoyed the culture of the other worlds, but the vast distances that separated their worlds meant that only a few dozen offworlders from the nearest worlds could make the decades-long trip to Guardian headquarters. Far Flier saw several familiar faces among those milling about and nodded to them.
Inside the entrance, the narrow hall flared and extended upward, like the inside of a gourd. The room had been designed so that a speaker standing near the narrow end would be heard equally by all inside, a throwback to the days when flocks of A’Nontans would congregate for song-drama and poetry festivals in which every voice had to be heard.
There were eight new cadets this year, but most of the staff turned out for these annual welcomings. The auditorium was packed.
“Good morning, new cadets,” Far Flier said. “And welcome to those of you who apparently have forgotten the speech that I give every year at this time, and came for a refresher.”
There was a low snicker from the audience. Far Flier rarely deviated from his set talk to the rookies. There was a small contingent at headquarters of Mintar, a mathematically oriented culture that loved gambling, and they ran an annual pool betting on how many new sentences there would be in his talk. The smart money had him at seven this year.
“And I will give a refresher of sorts,” he said. “I was intending to give my standard talk today, one I have honed over more than a century as the leader of the Guardian Council. And I will do some of that — it’s vital for you to begin with a firm understanding of our mission. Without that, the ensuing years you will spend acquiring our methods would be empty. And even our methods, it’s important to grasp their foundations and principles as well.
“But just this morning, something special and unusual happened and I think you will learn much from it. As you know, we seek to nurture emergent intelligent life. A few of you have such species on your own world, species that have evolved more slowly but now have all the hallmarks of intelligent life — abstraction, construction, complex social organization, and so on. But most of you have not had this experience. When we say ‘emergent intelligent life’ your enhancements will supply you with many facts and images of such species. But you will not know what their life really feels like to them. And if you don’t know that, you won’t be able to help them.
“Only a few hours ago, on a planet known to its inhabitants — the humans — as Earth, technologically driven warming caused fierce storms that created large waves in the ocean that covers three quarters of this world. These waves nearly killed a young man who is the strongest empath we have been able to discover on this planet. And for this emergent civilization, empathy is desparately required. The victims of these storms have now become the victims of their social system, bits of carrion to be preyed upon by the dominant members of their extended clan.
“And only a hundred or so meters from here, a Guardian ambassador has dedicated herself to helping this individual survive this crisis so that he has a chance to grow into a leader for his people. He has lost his home and is now a wandering migrant with thousands of others. He is at risk now, separated from the place and the social groupings that give his life context and a measure of protection. More than anything, he will feel disoriented because he has a strong need for connection that has been torn from its moorings.
 For the humans, an empath like this is as important to their future as the scientifically gifted were a thousand years ago. And this is where we make a difference. Does anyone know how?”
“Through connection?” ventured a spindly Javiranian.
“Yes, certainly,” Far Flier answered. “We connect, and in connecting, we bring the knowledge that connection is one of the deepest and most ancient qualities of life. To connect with naive individuals from species that only suspect that they are not alone in the universe, you will have to be practiced at it. You have all been born into a world filled with waveforms — your minds have always been connected with other minds in various ways.
“The human world doesn’t accept this as a general truth. Our human experiences his connections as an affliction. This crisis has pushed him forward. He now can sense the feelings of people around him. Later, perhaps, we will help him to go beyond that to the waveforms we enjoy — the vibrations that bring our thoughts to each other, that combined with our enhancements, give us a much richer experience of each other and of our species as a whole.
“To do that, you will have to master one of the two most important Guardian methods: entanglement.
“You have all learned the physics of entanglement. When the universe expanded and was no longer physically a single object, the force that connected everything in that primordial plasma remained a web throughout the universe, a web of quantum entanglement. We harness that to connect instantaneously by focusing energy through wormholes that bridge great spaces. This is how advanced species in our galaxy can connect, can be Guardians.
“On every world we have nurtured, we have found individuals who already have, usually unknown to them, great natural talents at connecting to that web of entanglement. Our young human is just such a person. People like him can take their species from an intellectual acknowledgment of how interdependent they are to a deep and functional understanding that will transform their worlds over the coming generations into something sustainable. Something beyond just achieving the technological ability to blow themselves up.
“Does that always work?” Low murmurs of “No” came from the cadets. “No, indeed. We have nurtured many species that were not able to cross that threshold to sustainable intelligence. What can we do to help them?”
“Send them back in time to start over,” replied a a burly tetrapod from Qualix.
“If only we could,” Far Flier said, smiling. “This is the most misunderstood of our two core capabilities. Our ability to entangle led us long ago to discover that our universe is really a multiverse. As the universe expanded, particles formed, and these particles existed in many simultaneous quantum possibilities, and each possibility created another universe. There are an enormous number of simultaneous universes, linked only by this web of entanglement. But they are only linked in the present, at the instant we connect.
“For millions of years after the Guardians were formed, we studied this phenomenon and were finally able to understand how to transmit and receive energy between these multiverses. And later, we learned how to transmit the energy that is a person’s consciousness to another part of the multiverse — a parallel universe, if you will — where they also exist.
“And that, my young Qualixian, is where the truth of your comment lies. We can send individuals to another present, to start over, to have a second chance. If any of you wind up working in our Timelines Department, you will learn how to map the many closely related universes that surround ours. You will learn how to assess which ones present the most favorable scenario, where self-destructive forces have coalesced a little more slowly, or where constructive trends have created more favorable conditions. And you will work with the ambassadors to transfer our contacts’ minds, the people we have entangled with, to those new timelines. They always retain some knowledge from their original universe, so they are able to act as change agents. But we cannot send them backwards or forwards in time. The universe forbids it.
“Well, I’ve gone on quite a bit. But it’s been a day that reminds me very powerfully of why we do what we do. That can be a rare gift; our work is patient and takes centuries to bear fruit. But when you see that we have the chance of a lifetime to help rescue an entire intelligent species from oblivion, it all makes sense. So welcome, and make the most of your time as a cadet. Ask all the questions you have. Give all the passion you feel.”
</Text>
