            <Title>The long game</Title>
            <Text>The Long Game
March 19, 2050
Far Flier had been dreading this day for months. But now that it was here, he felt oddly calm. Good, he thought, that is what my part of the waveform will feel like. At least he could rob Hanikori of the satisfaction of him being visibly humiliated in front of the council he had led for hundreds of year.
The department heads droned through their reports. For months, Far Flier had tried to rally Tanoch to some enthusiasm over Lina’s conversion of her village to sustain a waveform. Or to Raefe’s leverage of that waveform to make great strides in understanding how humanity’s social and biological evolution were interdependent. Tanoch, who had always been his strongest supporter, merely grunted and nodded with underwhelming enthusiasm. Far Flier had asked him point blank why he seemed so indifferent, but Tanoch hemmed and hawed and mumbled something about being overwhelmed by his imminent transformation to his species’ hermaphroditic phase.
Then their was Manulo, who had usually been a sensible council member. She was actually quite impressed with the Civilization Project’s final algorithms. Very advanced in some aspects, was how she had put it. Groundbreaking even. But Manulo, as always, was lost in her world of n-dimensional tensors and oblivious to the nuances of normal Council operations. She was barely 200 years old, so maybe time would teach her to engage more with other people. But for now, she saw Far Flier’s struggles as a distraction.
Far Flier knew that Hanikori had recruited Green and Putnomo to his plan. So it was him and two uninterested Council members against this band of three. Not really a winning hand. He suspected that Green might someday reject Hanikori — the young temporal engineer was basically an honest person and would have trouble with Hanikori’s sociopathic tendencies in the long run, he thought. But for today, he was onboard with Hanikori’s plan, which was becoming increasingly clear and alarming to Far Flier. He would keep that knowledge to himself and Diver, though, and continue to dig until he had the full measure of it.
Hanikori was the last of the department heads to give his report. Much ado about nothing, as usual. Maybe being the victim of the first coup in Guardian history isn’t so bad after all, he thought, if it means not having to let this claptrap into his mind.
“Thank you, Hanikori,” he said. “Council members, I want to thank you for your reports. And now I have my own report to give.”
There was a minor ripple in the waveform.
“You all know that Diver and I are having a child together. Sometime in the next decades, I will also transform to female. Both suggest that I can either miss the full joy of either to maintain my Council chair duties, or take another path. After more than 400 years in this role, I have decided to step down from both the chair and the council.”
“What will you do?” asked Green.
“I have some research projects that I’ve been working on slowly in the background  for years. And every Guardian Council chair tries to summarize the lessons of his or her tenure in their Annals, as part of our permanent record. Between that and my personal life, I think I will be productively busy.”
“As head of Administration, it falls to me to lead the process of picking a new chair,” Hanikori said. “In the meantime, I’m sure everyone here joins me in thanking you for your service.”
And with that, it was over. Hanikori had succeeded, Far Flier was still in the dark about what his final goal was, and the Guardians were entering one the most dangerous periods in hundreds of millenia.
