            <Title>The Wall</Title>
            <Text>Building a wall 
Raefe longed to be back in Nigeria with Lina. The weeks of being on the run in the British Isles had been wearying. His tolerance for cold and damp, so finely honed by his New England childhood, had disappeared during the years in Africa. A year ago, a trip to  Dutch Island would have had him thinking of beaches and sunshine, but he wasn’t sure how the winds that now blew down from Greenland  had changed the Low Islands. Well, it was work, not pleasure, anyway that had him standing at the customs queue at Port Hague.
Bye, bye, Tom Morgan, he thought as he presented his Nigerian passport. Back to the more practiced and familiar Rando Millard, irrigation technology sales representative for Soltech. If they checked, he had entered Northern England under that name. That should be good enough, given that the Dutch, like everyone else, would have no luck making sense out of movement between the two halves of the former England. Neither government recognized the other, nor would cooperate in even the most basic international procedures like border control. So illegal crossings were routine and accepted by the rest of Europe as normal.
Work would resume tomorrow, but for now he could relax and get a feel for the place.  He checked into the local Globo, which still had desk clerks.
“I have some time this afternoon,” he said to Rudi, a tall young man with classic Dutch features and a South Asian complexion. “What do you recommend?”
“The weather is still nice. Have you seen the Great Wall of Holland?”
“No, haven’t been here since it was built. I thought it was just a great big pile of Earth.” He’d been about to say dirt but caught himself.
“Yes, but it’s nearly 50 meters wide at the top and people have set up all sorts of things up there. Plus the view is pretty cool. You can grab a bike outside, or maybe there are some of the autonomous skateways if you’re tired. Just like an old skateboard, but they move on their own. Just tell it ‘Great Wall’ and you’re all set.”
Worst of both worlds, Raefe, thought, a self-driving skateboard. No fun and no comfort. He opted for the bike. This part of Port Hague was mostly the old Den Haag and there were no large vehicles.  He enjoyed zipping through narrow streets, feeling the still warm breeze on his face. Apocalypse was at bay for a little while.
He hadn’t expected much from the Great Wall — it actually sounded vaguely ridiculous to him. But it took his breath away at first glance.  He had seen vids, but they did it no justice. The Wall was more like a cliff, rising nearly 30 meters and extending as far as the eye could see. It was still under construction. The landward side already extensive gardens that would have pleased a Babylonian emperor. Raefe knew the flowers were there to draw bees, who would then also pollinate many of the food crops being grown in steep terrace gardens. Nonetheless it was quite a beautiful touch to the plain Dutch city.
A series of escalators running parallel to the face of the wall brought you to the various garden levels, and eventually, to the top. He stepped off onto a wide, grassy boulevard filled with all sorts of food stalls, dancers, jugglers, street singers and a busy assortment of people. He wanted to explore it all, but first he had to look out seaward. Well-marked paths took him to the western edge, where he could see North Sea waves crashing 20 meters below. If not for the wall, the water would have overwhelmed everything behind him. Now, as far as he could see to either side, the coast of Holland looked life the cliffs of Dover, but for the corkscrew wind generators attached every 20 meters or so.
He walked for nearly an hour, absorbing the sights and smells of life on the wall. The sea air made him hungry. He decided to try the local specialty, herring with chili sauce and fries with curried mayonnaise, washed down with zoutbier. He loved the herring — the chili cut perfectly through the salt and musk of the small fish. The curried fries were an acquired taste. And the beer made him sad. Fresh water was too precious to waste on beer now, so the great Dutch brewers had set out to perfect genetically modified yeast that could make beer from salt water. It was barely drinkable and made him yearn for an old-fashioned Heineken. For that alone, the corpos should be made to pay.
He let his mind wander among the crowd along the Wall and he felt a quiet strength and something almost like happiness. He couldn’t find a waveform to entangle with. The Dutch had so far resisted that kind of bond, something he hoped to begin to change with his meeting with Leader de Gruen tomorrow. While their minds might be unreadable, they weren’t closed. And then he felt a mild energy, a slight mental itch, almost as if someone was trying to find him. 
He suddenly felt alone and exposed, here in a country where he knew no one and was unprepared for adversity. What an idiot he head been to allow himself the luxury of coming up here. This Wall was nothing more than a trap, 300 kilometers of nowhere to hide. All the exits he could reach could be easily watched, giving him nowhere to run either. He was about to reach out to Lina when a hand touched his shoulder from behind. He turned to face a young man.
“Raefe Miller?”
“No, I’m afraid you’re mistaken.” His mind raced, trying to buy time to decide what to do.
“Ah yes, Herr Millard. Not to worry — Leader de Gruen sent me to look after you. We should leave here now, you may not be safe.”
“Ok, what do I do?”
“Put these on.” He handed Raefe a Zon, the popular Dutch straw hat for sun protection and a pair of sunglasses.
“There, now you look like a local,” the man said. “Now we’ll walk up to escalator 14, which is the busiest on the wall. My name is Tygo, by the way.”
“Nice to meet you,” Raefe said, not meaning it all. He was rattled by how easily he had been found. “How did you find me?”
“I’ve been following you since you landed,” he said.
“You are very good at it,” Raefe said. “I never noticed you.”
“Just the point, eh,” Tygo said, smiling. “But I think you did, in a way.”
“That was you, that little tingle I felt in my mind?”
“Yes, I have a bit of the empath. I don’t need to see you to know where you are. But perhaps you have also felt one or two people who are looking for you, who are not so friendly?”
“Truthfully, no. I guess the world is catching up to me — outside of Nigeria, I’m so used to being the rare empath. I often sit in parks and let my mind wander outwards. I don’t usually find anyone who’s aware of me. On some level, I’ve been waiting for this day, with some dread. Turnabout is fair play, I suppose.”
“Fair play is not what is at stake, though, is it?” Tygo said. “I can teach you how to evade me later, but for now, we should go.”
“Lead on.”
He followed the Dutchmen through a mystifyingly innocuous yet purposeful series of turns and stops. Tygo urged silence, answering none of Raefe’s questions, whether spoken or thought. They were almost at the escalator when Raefe felt a sudden spike of anger wash over him from somewhere off to the left. He looked quickly in that direction, but could see nothing. He felt Tygo’s hand on his shoulder, and turned to see him shaking his head “no,” and felt the Dutchmen’s hand gently pushing him toward the escalator.
They descended in silence. Raefe started toward his bicycle but again Tygo shook his head.
“It is a public bike — let’s leave it here and travel in more comfort,” Tygo said, pointing toward a small solar three wheeler. So the stern bodyguard had a sense of humor after all, Raefe thought. They nestled into the tiny vehicle and told it to go to the Globo.
“Can we talk in here?” Raefe asked.
“Yes, we are safe now from prying minds and ears,” he answered.
“How much danger were we in?” Raefe asked. “I thought I felt someone angry and frustrated near the escalator.”
“Quite so, but he wasn’t alone. I believe there were three men and two women up there looking for you,” Tygo said. “They seemed to not know where you were in Den Haag, and were up there on the assumption that you might visit. So now I think we have left them behind and they are none the wiser.”
“I can’t believe that I didn’t sense them. I must be getting old!”
“No, but perhaps you are not practiced at deception. It goes against your beliefs about empathy.”
Raefe felt slightly sick. Empathic deception — what did that even mean? He would very much have to look into this.
“We are at your hotel. Tomorrow, then. You are with Herr deGruen at 11. I will come at nine and we will spend some time teaching you to hide in plain thought, as it were.”</Text>
