            <Title>Maximum liquidity</Title>
            <Text>Maximum liquidity
Diver loved sitting on this rock after fishing. She had her own name for it — Hawk’s Perch — but she knew Far Flier would think it sentimental and silly, so it remained her private name for it. Whatever he might think, it was a good name for this solitary rock, standing 20 meters high just off the beach. From the top, she could see the silver flash of bait fish far out into the water, the ripples where blue trout disturbed those schools, and the swells of Adno’s people as they herded the blue trout into the shallows, where they could feast on them as needed.
She had her own ways of hunting the blue trout, flying above them and grasping them in her enhanced claws or even her mouth. They had lived for millions of years without fear from the skies, so they rarely looked up. This morning’s harvest had filled her basket, which  held two days food for them. She could relax and let Water Eye’s warm rays dry her. This world’s star was larger and brighter than A’Nonto’s but it was alone in the day sky. After 30 years, she was finally getting used to the simple, repetitive cycle of day and night. There was something clean and direct about this diurnal existence, but she sometimes missed the more varied kinds of light that the dance of Mother,  the two Fathers and the Twins had brought to the world she had been born and spent her first 450 years on.
She had been surprised at how hard it had been to accommodate to this new place. Her mind had traveled so many places through the wormhole interface network, she hadn’t understood that it would be different to stand on a different piece of rock, with a different sky. But she shuddered to think about what would have happened had she and Far Flier not taken their child and disappeared, avoiding Hanikori’s sharp beak, at least figuratively. Antithikos was very young when they had come here, and he took to it well enough. When he was hungry, when he wanted to sleep, to be most active — these became the new rhythms of their life. When she and Far Flier had bred Marilon, they spent much time in the water. 
After she was born, Mari took to the water like an alaktar, the water birds of their home world. Even her enhancements adapted themselves to be as adept on the surface and under the water as on land. For Far Flier and her, it was a pleasant and surprising reminder of just how flexible life can be, a message they had perhaps needed in their sometimes lonely exile. As she trudged up the hill to their home with her basket of fish, she felt her family’s minds begin to brush hers. Long ago, she had glimpsed an image in one of the human’s minds — was it Raefe or Lina — from an Earth story about someone living all alone in a forest who kept a candle in the window in case strangers were looking for warmth in the cold nights of their winter. That’s what her brood’s minds felt like just now.
“You’ve been fishing,” Anti greeted her. “My fierce mother.”
“Fierce?” she protested. “So you only want to eat leaves now?”
“Why don’t you let Adno’s school bring us fish?” Mari asked. “It’s nothing for them.”
“I do,” she said. “I let them bring us things from the deeps and from the bottom, things we cannot get for ourselves. I like fishing.”
“We should teach our children to hunt, don’t you think,” Far Flier said, laughing at the whole familiar conversation. “What kind of A’Mopto is it who must ask fish to feed them?”
“The kind who lives on the world of the fish,” Anti shot back, who was always embarrassed at his parents insistence on maintaining their old rituals from their old home, a home fading from his memory and never seen by his sister.
“If that bastard Hantikori falls in a volcano someday, we should take a chance on you both joining the waveform back there,” Diver said. “I love this world, and I’m so grateful for Adno and her school to take us in, but I worry that you don’t get to feel so many of the joys we had growing up on A’Nonto.”
“Wouldn’t that be nice,” Far Flier agreed, knowing it was better to agree with her than remind her how unlikely that was. “But the children and I have been talking with Adno and she brings news from the Guardians.”
“Oh,” Diver replied. “Good or bad?”
“Well, likely bad,” Far Flier said. “Hantikori is re-organizing the Council. She’s not clear what it all means, except that it seems to mean that the Council will both look less for new contacts and be more intrusive with the ones they have.”
“Intrusive,” she said with some alarm. “In what way?”
“Unknown,” he said. “But he’s brought back the old ideas of more direct intervention. Maybe even technology transfers.”
“He’s a madman,” Diver said. “Every 10,000 years or so, some madman like him steers the Guardians in that direction and it never ends well.”
“Much worse, actually, than you may know,” Far Flier said. “In the distant past, some of these misguided leaders actually brought about the destruction of entire species due to their meddling.”
“Oh, Far Flier, I can’t bear it. Stuck hear on this island, cut off from the waveform, watching your life’s work, and what was to be mine, dissolved in an acid of egotism and foolishness. Even after these eons of learning and peace, to know that this can still happen.”
“Wisdom is no more solid than this island,” he said. “Battered by waves of all sorts. But you know that. I sense that something more specific is bothering you.”
“Walking up the hill, I remembered a little story from Raefe’s mind. I miss the humans, I miss the freshness and boldness of their struggles. We have so much built up knowledge and technology and the help of 20 other races to guide us. They have none of that, yet they are so firm in fighting for their own future. Even when they are wrong, their passion wins my heart. I can’t bear to think of what will happen to them if Hanikori and his foolish little clique meddle in their world.”
“We’ll have to trust that Adno can prevent that,” he said, but she could see in his eyes that he was worried as well.


</Text>
