            <Title>Island Life</Title>
            <Text>Island life
Jan de Gruen was the first Leader of the Dutch Island Republic. His title set him apart from the 1,000 Delegates and the 50 Councillors who formed the political government of the new nation, but he was as much a follower of the Delegates and Councillors as their Leader. Raefe was comforted to feel that he was internally strong but also comfortable, not looking to establish dominance in their dealings.
“Welcome, Herr Miller,” de Gruen said. “I understand you had a close call on the Wall yesterday?”
“So I’m told. Your man Tygo was a bit mysterious about it all. But efficient. I did sense one or two people in the crowd near the escalator who were hostile, although I could not locate them.”
“Ah, the famous empath in action. Very good, by the way.”
“Your man was much better at it. I have a lot to learn from him. That surprised me, I have to admit. I generally think of your country as uninterested in entangling.”
“But always interested in engaging with other people on their own terms,” DeGruen said. “But seriously, our surveillance bots identified two women who we know to be corpo agents at that location. Do you recognize them?”
Two faces appeared on the wall, common Euro Asian appearance.
“Never seen them. Noticed you’re not wearing a puter. You’ve been modded?”
De Gruen winced. “I just think of it as an implant. Still the same me, otherwise.”
“Interesting. You’re the first person outside of fairly high level corpos who I’ve met with that.”
“Well, you have your empathy, we have our circuitry.”
“I wish it were that simple. But before we get into that, what do you think these agents were up to?”
“We’re not sure. We know they work for Philips DeMag. The corpos are quite disturbed about our meeting. They have inside sources and they have some idea about what we’re going to discuss.”
“I’ve been discussing active empathic skills training around the world for decades. The corpos don’t like it, but why the sudden panic?”
De Gruen smiled. “With all due respect to your talents and vision, we also have some ideas that could really shake up the whole world, right now.”
“I’m all ears.”
“Many people involved in the whole Dutch Republic project have turned their minds to what’s next now that the Wall has us safe from the sea, at least for this century. If the snows come, we’ll have more challenges, but for now, we are safe. But the whole Wall project was very revealing to many Dutch people.”
“In what way?
“It made them think about territory. The Netherlands were a nation that was always growing, but only slightly, larger — reclaiming land from the sea, building walls and dikes. We maintained a balance between people and land. Now our land is shrinking.”
“Partly your choice, don’t you think? Building the Dutch Channel between yourself and Philips Free State — what did you expect?”
“Just so. Most of our citizens call it Philips Not So Free State, and they were happy to put a mile of sea water between us. And now, What can we do? Stop letting people in? Throw some people out? Mandate a one child, or no child, policy, as China disastrously did generations ago? None of these appeal to our citizens, yet here we are.”
“I don’t need to sense your thoughts to know you have arrived at a plan. What is it?”
“The world is full of a growing number of stateless people. You’ve seen the “1B” logos on clothes everywhere. More than a billion people have left not just their home, but their countries, in the last five years, driven by flood, lack of water, corporate tyranny, and good old-fashioned dictatorial government, ethnic and religious strife, and a long list of other things. It’ll be two billion before long. What will become of these people, with no state to defend them?”
“Obviously you know of my work with Nowhere. They grew out of exactly this problem, during the many years of conflict in  Africa. Now millions of Africans are Citizens of Nowhere.”
“Yes, we have followed your work with Lina Kawambai Yang over the last three decades quite closely. When the NVA and Nowhere joined forces in 2055, you created a brilliant solution for many Africans. Their societies’ development was gutted. It seemed like every time they came close to reversing the effects of colonialism, they faced an equal challenge from corporate invaders, local despots, climate change and ongoing civil strife. Your combination of effective technology and new arrangements for governance really cut through all of that. But I think you’d admit that the Free Alliance you’ve tried to build on top of that around the world is going slowly.”
“You’re right about that. We continue to try new things. Do you have some thoughts on the Free Alliance?”
“Living in the heart of Europe, with UFS a boat ride away, Philips a kayak ride away, and several other global corpo powers a train ride away, we are  keenly aware that the corpos believe the world has reached a tipping point. Governments are weak enough, and the corpos are strong enough, to reverse the power relationship.”
“You mean they want to put a bullet in the head of the governments they’ve spent two centuries bullying and controlling.”
“Something like that. We think they will make a move soon.”
“You’re referring to the summit in Lausanne next month?”
“Very impressive, Herr Miller. Few people know of it.”
“Do you know what they have planned?”
“Not precisely. But in broad terms, we expect them to divide the world into territories, rather like a corporate salesforce has, and each of the major corpos is expected to control those territories. Their goal is just to maximize profit. They’ll allow civil governments to continue collecting the garbage and so on, but no decisions with significant  impact on either the corpos or their leadership corps will be taken without their approval. Profit is their main concern — petty issues like morality will be left to those who have such ethereal concerns.”
“The fools. After what they’ve done to the world for 200 years, they shouldn’t be able to get a job as a data clerk, let alone running the world. They’ll make a hash of it.”
“Quite. More to the point, they’ll make more of a hash of our world. Conceivably, they could push the warming past merely hostile into uninhabitable. Their inability to sacrifice short-term gain for long-term benefits suggests, in fact, that the most likely outcome of another 200 years of corpo rule will be the end of Earth as broadly habitable. Not that the most powerful of them will suffer. They are already exploring underground living in Dubai, and soon we’ll hear about their plans for space villages.”
“But, let’s be honest, Herr de Gruen, they’ve been headed this way for a long time. And you still haven’t told me what your plan is.”
“It’s Pietr, by the way. Our plan is very simple. The Dutch Republic is going to announce in a month’s time that it will become the first global nation. Any person in the world can become a citizen of the Dutch Republic. We ask only that you pay us a tax of 10% of your income above 100,000 euros. In exchange, you will receive a passport from us and one vote. We will guarantee you basic social benefits — unemployment insurance, health insurance and old-age benefits — and represent you in legal disputes with the corpos and other governments. Only humans can be citizens — no corporations,  or animal surrogates for them, no computers.”
“Very interesting. And how do you think the Free Alliance fits into this?”
“The forces allied with you are natural allies for us. We want to work together. Many things are on the table — dual citizenship for Nowhere, strategic alliances. We know you have contacts with other emerging forces around the world in the Free Alliance. The Global Republic of Holland is just a beginning. Where can we go together?”
“That is something I will be happy to discuss with Nowhere’s governing council, and others in the Free Alliance.  Perhaps the question should be how can we do things that no country has ever done? How can we break down the social divisions that make war, famine, and social dominance by certain groups possible, even inevitable?”
“And we are attracted by your vision in those areas. So let us begin the discussion.”
</Text>
