            <Title>Earth, Too</Title>
            <Text>Earth, too
Marilon found the blue trout just beyond the reef. Their thoughts were very rudimentary, but Adno had taught her to recognize them. The blue trout had a deep fear of the Reef Gardners — what Adno’s kind called themselves — and they always maintained an awareness of where to avoid them.
Today, the trout were relaxed. The Reef Gardners were neither on the reef nor gardening. They had gone deep, off the shelf, looking for the shellfish who lived near the sulfur and phosphorous vents. Every so often, they hunted them for the minerals that their bodies required. Marilon floated to the surface and let Water Eye dry her. She re-adjusted her enhancements, extending the webs between her toes and fingers, and allowing her feathers to regenerate on her arms. The whole process took about five minutes, by which time she was mostly dry.
She flapped her arms hard enough to raise her up on her feet on the water. She let her webbed feet catch the water as she zipped quickly along the surface. In a single fluid motion as she ran, she raised her arms just over her shoulders, and then thrust downward mightily, and tucked her feet under her. She was airborne now and quickly found the wind that circled upward from the water toward the sun. She headed toward where the trout had pointed to Adno’s school.
A few minutes later, she could see them below the water, their silver blue bodies reflecting the sun back. Her mother often reminisced about the beautiful green and black of the fish on their old world. Fish with shiny backs had long ago been consumed by her kind, leaving only the dark-backed behind. But flyers had never evolved on this world, where 95% of the surface was water. Near the surface, there was nothing larger or more dangerous than the  three-meter-long Reef Gardners, so they put on a brilliant underwater show for Marilon in the bright sun.
Marilon slipped into the school’s waveform as she circled down to the surface. She was far from their little island now, truly alone on the surface of the great sea.
“Mari who sits on the water,” Adno’s thoughts reached out to her. “The Reef Gardners invite you to add your darkness to our light.”
“Many thanks,” she responded. “But I come to seek your wisdom, Guardian Ambassador.”
“Then join me and we will let the warm river take us to quiet waters,” Adno replied.
Marilon shifted her enhancements again, slimming her wings and activating her underwater breathing capabilities. Her eyes shifted slightly toward the infrared. She could see the school below. She dove under, heading for the warm current rising from an ocean floor vent that Adno had mentioned. Quick as a flash, Adno was along side of her, nuzzling her with her snout.
“You are far from home,” Adno said. “I sense that you are troubled.”
“Far Flier says that there is trouble with the Guardians. He worries about Earth. Should I be worried?”
Adno circled, her dorsal fin shaking slightly in the way she showed uncertainty or unease.
“I wish I knew, little water bird. The older ones on the Council have changed things, for the better they say. Since your mother left, I have tried my best, but Earth is my first assignment as Ambassador. Tanoch has helped me, and I feel that I have helped Raefe and Lina in various ways. But now Tanoch has left the Council and never joins the waveform from his home planet anymore. Green — he is your kind — thinks soothing thoughts when we entangle, but he seems more interested in pleasing Hanikori than anything else. And that man makes me feel that somewhere  in the cold water below, a big predator is watching me.”
“The humans have a saying about people like him — he’s a snake.”
“A snake?”
“Yes, they are the land equivalent of a kanna eel. Like the kanna hides in the reef, and then darts out and poisons you, the snake hides in the grass or rocks on land and also has a poisonous bite.”
“Well, that snake has a very big head and he doesn’t hide much. Since your father left, he has changed everything. Still, I don’t think he’s done and now that I think of it, you’re right. He hides many things, including what the future holds for Earth.”
“My parents don’t know that Anti and I have joined with Des and Nyssa through the waveform. I don’t think Raefe and Lina know either. But I can’t bear to think of something bad happening to all of them.”
“Young one, your parents are not so old that they would not understand your affection for the humans. But that is for you to tell them, not me. I will keep you informed.”
“Maybe we should do more than that, Adno. You’re on you’re own on the Council. You have to stay there so we know what’s happening. But you may have to keep quiet to do that.”
“What are you saying?”
“That Anti and I can be your surrogate. All three of us can figure it out. Green never has to know. You can play along with him, keep him in the dark.”
“You are asking me to betray the Guardian Council.”
“I think Far Flier would say you would be acting as a true Guardian.”
“I have to think about that, Mari. But I will keep it between us.”
“Thanks, Adno. I’m going to the surface to dry off now, so I can fly home.”
“Fly well, bird whose feathers are not always the color they seem.”
That night, in the faint gray orange that was night on Water Eye, she found an excuse for Anti and her to go for a walk. Once out of her parents’ sight, they walked down the narrow trail that led to a small cave. As small children, they had found this cave and it had become their secret place, almost the only place that on their little island that their parents couldn’t see them.
Once inside, she told Anti about her conversation with Adno.
“What are you worried about?” Anti asked. “I mean, specifically, what do you think the Guardians would do to mess up Earth?”
“You know that both mom and dad think that ‘Kori is a psycho, right? That when he was Earth Ambassador, some pretty weird shit happened on the planet.”
“True. I see your point. We have to tell Des and Nyssa, don’t you think?”
“I do,” Mari said. “I think, in fact, that the four of us have to be prepared to step in. No one on the Council knows about us. They probably don’t think too much about Des and Nyssa. All of us live to be thousands of years old, so it’s only natural that they think of Des and Nyssa as little more than newborns. And even mom and dad don’t know that I was part of the Reef Gardner waveform, and our family’s, before I was born. And that after I learned how to modify my enhancements, I taught you. So we have abilities that are new, maybe, even to the Guardians.”
“I see your point. For now, let’s not freak Des and Nyssa out too much. Let’s just introduce the idea that we’re all going to pay attention to anything unusual, anything on Earth that smells like Guardian.”</Text>
