            <Title>Playing telephone</Title>
            <Text>Playing telephone
“Can you believe this?” Antithikos said, his thoughts tinged with anger. “This Hantikori is really just too much.”
“This is outrageous, for sure,” Des replied. “But being on the exact planet that he seems to be trying to manipulate, I’m worried about what we can do to prevent this from happening.”
“We have to tell Raefe and Lina,” Nyssa said.
“Can you do that without getting into how the four of us learned this?” Marilon asked. “Or are we ready to let them know that we can entangle with each other from Water Eye to Earth without the Guardian wormhole network? And that we could entangle with the people in that room without them knowing it?”
“Mom and Dad already know that there’s something extra in how me and Des communicate,” Nyssa said.
“They do?” Des asked. “When did that happen?”
“Just recently I told them that we can tell when they entangle. I told them it’s one of those twin things. I joined in one of their ‘conference calls’ and just let it drop. Sorry, I should have told you.”
“We’ve kept it all from our parents,” Marilon said. “They haven’t even quite figured out that Adno entangles with her school in quite a different way than with Mom and Dad. Far Flier will never get his head around it, I’m afraid. Mom will though — she’s always been in touch her ‘bird’ side, she likes the different feeling she gets from it.”
“Let’s keep the big picture in mind here,” Antithikos said. “The head of the Guardian Council has deceived one of the most powerful human beings, who now thinks he has some kind of imaginary friend named Hank. And Hank has manipulated Billy Warren into creating an alliance of his fellow oligarchs by promising them the technology to live hundreds of years and to do it in secret underground, self-sufficient settlements while the humans above destroy the environment and themselves. We can’t allow that to happen! This is exactly what drove my parents off our home world. Mari, I know you think Far Flier’s a funny old man, but he’s fought for centuries to keep stuff like this from happening.”
“You’re right, Anti,” she said. “Des, Nyssa, do we come out to our parents?”
Their waveform rang with agreement.
*****
Lina bolted awake. Raefe’s slow slide into sleep ended abruptly. Far Flier and Diver’s picnic lunch on a particularly picturesque cliff was interrupted. Suddenly the four of them had joined the waveform their children had created. It was somehow stronger and more vivid than their normal connections.
“Mom, Dad, Raefe, Lina,” Anti said. “The four of us have some news for you that’s urgent. I know you’ll have many questions, and we can talk afterwards, but there’s some things you must know.”
The four older ones murmured their assent, alarmed and puzzled.
“When I was young, and we were back on A’Nonto, I knew that you were in danger from Hanikori,” Anti continued. “I guess because I was so young and still mastering entanglement, I became very sensitive to his signature in the waveform. It was like he was a scary monster and I wanted to know where he was at all times. Later I learned some other skills and well, the long and short of it is that I basically can entangle with Hanikori at will, without him knowing. In other words, I’ve been watching him since we’ve been on Water Eye.”
“Don’t you realize how dangerous that is?” Far Flier said. “His people control the wormhole interface network, they record all the signatures. He probably knows you’re doing this. And where you are — he can come after you if he wants.”
“Like I said, there’s a lot we have to tell you,” Anti continued. “But for now, no, he can’t. I can connect with him outside of the Guardian network. In fact, we’re all connected that way right now.”
There was a moment of stunned silence as that sunk in.
“Right, so here’s what we know. During ‘Kori’s term as Ambassador to Earth, he developed a thing for powerful humans with little or no empathy. Since he forced you both off of the Council, he convinced himself that Adno, because she’s so physically different than humans, couldn’t possibly be a good ambassador, so he gave her that job. He thinks she’s unaware of what’s going on.”
“And is she?” Diver asked.
“No,” Anti replied. “It’s true that she doesn’t get every nuance of what land dwellers do or think. But she’s just as capable of entangling with humans as you. Raefe and Lina, I believe you have had occasional contact with her?”
