            <Text>Wired for thought
“You told us that Warren had turned the whole summit upside down with his proposal,” Raefe said. “But how did the others react?”
“Somewhat mixed,” Des said. “The Euros were skeptical — they’re up against some of the most organized citizen movements. There wasn’t even anyone from Africa there, by the way, so they’ve ceded that to Nowhere.  Robertson was thrilled — he actually believes all that meritocracy crap, not to mention that he thinks he’s got more merit than the rest of us. The rest mostly fell in line.”
“But even the Euros agreed,” Nyssa said. “On paper, they’re all in.”
“What do you think their timetable is?” Raefe asked.
“Not worked out yet,” Nyssa replied. “That’s the thing — we’re totally in the dark about anything specific. You know how these guys are — I’ll have my computer call your computer.”
“How do we find out more?” Lina asked. “We need to plan a counterattack. I think we need to gather our forces soon — NVA, the Dutch, everyone in or near the Free Alliance.”
“Agreed,” said Raefe. “But we can’t just tell them what we know now and say, ‘hey, what do you think we should do?’ That will be chaos. We need more insight into their plan.”
“Do you think Manfred would  meet with you again?” asked Des. “I have an idea.”
“I think he would,” said Raefe. “Especially if I give him some sense that his bosses are involved in something new and more awful.”
******
Cathedral Square was packed with Barceloni. Nyssa had carefully chosen a small cafe in front of a nondescript boutique hotel in the far corner of the square. From here, she could see all entrances to the square. Manfred might recognize her, but wouldn’t notice Des in a million years. Her brother was sitting on a blanket selling souvenirs just outside the church with a little sign around his neck indicating he was deaf. Raefe had accumulated some pretty tough acquaintances in his recent travels around western Europe and half a dozen of them were scattered around. If Manfred was playing her, he’d regret it quickly.
She had spent the day before shopping for just the right clothes for a young Barcelona woman. In her dark red harem pants, vintage Jordans,  cropped Real Catalan team shirt, and a sheer white headscarf, she fit right in. She could see Manfred scanning the square for her. She had expected the full masterful young corpo get up on him, but he was dressed down in shorts and sandles. She let him search for awhile, reaching out to touch his mind. He was outwardly calm but a little tense inside. To be expected, she thought. If he was part of some plan to kidnap her, he was better at hiding his emotions than she imagined he should be. Finally, she made eye contact and waved him over.
“Look at you,” he said, “a proper little Barca girl.”
“And you,” she answered, “slumming with the tourists. Been awhile, eh?”
“Yeah, I saw your dad last year, but what’s it been, ten years now?”
“Just about. You’re looking well.”
“And you! Nigeria must agree with you.”
“Most days, yes. Dad says Europe has had its ups and downs for you.”
“More like ups and then downs,” he nodded a bit ruefully. “Here in Catalan, you can’t really feel the tremors that are shaking up the rest of Europe. It’s a bit like the last glacier in the Swiss Alps — you can hear it groaning and cracking in the distance but you don’t know whether it will just melt away, or come tumbling down on the villages below. Back in Philips DeMag, you can watch the ice tumble down the mountainside from your kitchen window, as it were.”
“ Where do you think things are going, Manfred?”
Manfred gazed out over the plaza, eyes strangely vacant. She was just about to clear her throat to jog him back when he abruptly turned to her.
“You think that because I have neural implants and have some minor responsibility in the technocracy, that I know things like ‘where it’s all headed.’ I don’t. I hear things, I can guess things. That’s all.”
“Nyssa, I’ve been monitoring his mind,” Des said from a distance. “He was just connected back to Philips’ computer network. Looking something up. Couldn’t tell what.”
“We’re not in danger?” she asked. “He wasn’t signaling someone?”
“No I don’t think so,” Des said. “But I’m paying attention. What I need you to do is get him to access the network again. I think I can hack the system through him.”
“Sorry,” Nyssa said, turning her attention back to Manfred. “Don’t take it the wrong way. I think of you as a friend. We’re all caught up in this. Last century, they had a saying — ‘rearranging deck chairs on the Titanic’— and I don’t want to be that person. None of us do, to be the person yelling ‘Water!’ as the ship sinks. Anything you can tell me that will help us avoid that is very much appreciated.”
“My boss’s boss took part in some kind of big corpo meeting recently,” he said. “I told Raefe about it months ago.”
“Right, in Lausanne. We know who was there, but not what came  of it.”
“You can expect that there were layers to it. The first layer is a big public show of a plan to show they’re on top of things. After that, things get murkier.  And more threatening.”
“How so?”
“The corpos’ business model has evolved as the crisis has deepened. Fifty years ago, their model was get as much money out of the system in the short term as they could. But then they realized that governments were weakening faster than them and their model switched to fostering global privatization, with the top corpos consolidating regional power. Nowhere, the NVA, the Dutch Republic, all the smaller imitators — they’re eating into the corpo revenue stream. And the costs are rising with the waters and the droughts and the rest of it.”
“So, a new business model? Is that what Lausanne was about?”
“Precisely. I don’t know all of the details but I know where they are stored. I know you have people who can hack their way in.”
“I wouldn’t know about that,” she smiled. “But if you want to message me with links to where I might learn more, I’ll see what sense I can make out of it.”
“I”ll do better than that. I’m going to transfer some info to a neutral server. Later I’ll send you a key. Than a location. I have to spread it out to avoid the security bots.”
He got that far away look in his eyes again.
“There, it’s done. Expect the rest within 48 hours.”
Des was telling her that he had got what they needed. “Thanks, Manfred,” she said. “I know this can’t be easy for you. And if you need asylum, you know where to find it.”
“Thanks, Nyssa,” he said, a touch of sadness in his voice. “I feel like that old Greek myth about the kid who flew too close to the sun. We can never lead the life we should have, you know?”
“But we can leave the life we shouldn’t live,” she said. “Just say the word.”
“You take care,” he said, abruptly standing. He squeezed her shoulder and walked off without a glance backward.
</Text>
