            <Text>Maximum liquidity
Water Eye
September 21, 2081

Diver loved sitting on this rock after fishing. She had her own name for it — Hawk’s Haven — but she knew Far Flier would think it sentimental and silly, so it remained her private name. Whatever Far Flier might think, it was a good name for this solitary rock, standing 20 meters high just off the beach. From the top, she could see the silver flash of bait fish far out into the water, the ripples where blue trout disturbed those schools, and the swells of Adno’s people as they herded the blue trout into the shallows, where they could feast on them as needed.
 She stripped off her flight suit, lounging on the rocks while Prime dried her. At first, the sky had seemed nothing like Traveller’s Perch, even though it was the same solar system. But after 30 years, it had become just as familiar as the view of her first 450 years.
She had been surprised at how hard it had been to accommodate to this new place. Her mind had traveled so many places through the wormhole interface network, she hadn’t understood how different it would be to stand on a different piece of rock, with a different sky. But she shuddered to think about what would have happened had Adno not warned them of Hanikori’s plot. She and Far Flier had been paralyzed by the news, but Adno had already arranged a “supervisory” visit from them and a convenient failure of their ship, preventing them returning. Hanikori had at first insisted on rescuing him, but they made a very public plea to remain on this world, they loved it too much to leave. He had been forced to drop the matter and settle for their permanent exile from Traveller’s Perch.
 Antithikos had just been born when they had come here, and he took to it well enough. When he was hungry, when he wanted to sleep, when he wanted to play — these became the new rhythms of their life. A few years later, just before Far Flier had undergone her transformation to female, the two of them had bred Marilon. They spent much time in the water, hoping to acclimate her to it. And it had worked.
After she was born, Mari took to the water like an alaktar, the marine birds of their home world. Diver, Anti and Flier were typical A’Nontans, broad across the shoulders and long in the arms but slight in the legs and feet, even if not as slight or long-armed as their ancestors. Mari was longer in the leg and shorter in the arm — a swimmer’s build. Even her enhancements adapted themselves to be as adept in and on water as on land and in the air. For Far Flier and Diver, it was a pleasant and surprising reminder of just how flexible life can be, a message they had perhaps needed in their sometimes lonely exile. 
As she trudged up the hill, she could see the place they’d called home for these many years. When they had come, Adno’s people had adapted the typical Water Eye underwater reef structure for them, grown from engineered corals. Diver and Flier had rigged up a system of pulleys and ramps to bring it out of the water and up here on the ridge in the middle of their small island. They had become the first intelligent land dwellers on Water Eye. Unlike their homes on  Traveller’s Perch, it didn’t morph to meet their needs. It had taken some getting used to, living in a structure that never changed. But then, they had changed it in little ways, decorating it with shells and branches and pieces of the bright blue stone that stuck out from the rock here and there on their island.
Her reminiscing about creating their home was interrupted by as her family’s minds begin to brush hers. Long ago, she had glimpsed an image in one of the human’s minds — was it Raefe or Lina? — from an Earth story about someone living all alone in a forest who kept a candle in the window in case strangers were looking for warmth in the cold nights of their winter. That’s what her brood’s minds felt like just now.
“My fierce mother mother,” Anti greeted her. “You’ve been fishing.”
“Fierce?” she protested. “So you only want to eat leaves now?”
“Why don’t you let Adno’s school bring us fish?” Mari asked. “It’s nothing for them. I can even swim out to them and retrieve it so they don’t need to come all the way here.”
“I do let them bring us things,” she said. “I let them bring us things from the deeps and from the bottom, things we cannot get for ourselves. I like fishing.”
“We should teach our children to hunt, don’t you think,” Flier said, laughing at the whole familiar conversation. “What kind of person is it who must ask another species to feed them?”
“The kind who lives on the world of water, father mother,” Anti shot back, who was always embarrassed at his parents’ insistence on maintaining their old rituals from their old world, a home fading from his memory and never seen by his sister.
“If that bastard Hantikori falls in a volcano someday, we should take a chance on you both joining the waveform back there,” Diver said. “I love this world, and I’m so grateful for Adno and her school to take us in, but I worry that you don’t get to feel so many of the joys we had growing up on Prime.”
“Wouldn’t that be nice,” Flier agreed, knowing it was better to agree with her than remind her how unlikely that was. “But the children and I have been talking with Adno and she brings news from the Guardians.”
“Oh,” Diver replied. “Good or bad?”
“Well, likely bad,” Flier said. “Hantikori is bringing back the old ideas of more direct intervention. Maybe even technology transfers.”
“He’s a fool,” Diver said. “Every 10,000 years or so, some madman like him steers the Guardians in that direction and it never ends well.”
“Much worse, actually, than you may know,” Flier said. “In the distant past, some of these misguided leaders actually brought about the destruction of entire species due to their meddling.”
“I can’t stand it! Stuck hear on this island, cut off from the waveform, watching your life’s work, and what was to be mine, dissolved in an acid of egotism and foolishness. Even after these eons of learning and peace, to know that this can still happen.”
“Wisdom is no more solid than this island,” Flier replied. “Battered and worn by waves of all sorts. But you know that. I sense that something more specific is bothering you.”
“Walking up the hill, I remembered a little story from Raefe. I miss the humans, I miss the freshness and boldness of their struggles. We have so much built up knowledge and technology and the help of 19 other races to guide us. They have none of that, yet they are so firm in fighting for their own future. Even when they are wrong, their passion wins my heart. I can’t bear to think of what will happen to them if Hanikori and his foolish little clique meddle in their world.”
“We’ll have to trust that Adno can prevent that,” Far Flier said, but Diver could see in her eyes that she was worried as well.
“Our moms are distraught,” Anti thought, letting only Mari know. “It’s painful to feel them.”
“Exiles on a world they don’t really understand, robbed of the purpose they prepared centuries for,” Mari answered. “I want to tell them that it’s not as hopeless as they think.”
“Yes, it’s time,” Anti agreed. He opened his thoughts again to his parents. “Don’t count out Adno. She is more powerful than you think.”
“I know you admire her,” Diver said. “But she’s just one person.”
“No, she’s not,” Mari said. “She’s one person among a whole school. We used to fly as flock, but even then, we were solitary much of the time. Not Adno’s people. They live their entire lives in the school, all the time.”
“What are you saying?” Far Flier said.
“That Adno’s people have their own waveform, always did,” Mari answered, “long before they joined the Guardians and mastered the wormhole interface network. Their far distant ancestors evolved from giant sentient mats of many kinds of micro-organisms, all entangled in a primitive network. The comets that broke up those networks did not destroy that — they only divided the mats into smaller mats, each of which evolved in its own way. One branch continued to evolve and became the schools. They have always been entangled. The water around them carries their smells and vibrations and the echoes of the electricity in their brains. She has the wisdom and strength of her whole school, and sometimes, her whole species.”
Diver suddenly understood the many small things that had puzzled her for years. “You’ve learned to join that, Mari, haven’t you?” she said.
“I always knew. When you and father mother would swim with me inside you before I was born, I wasn’t just learning to entangle with you.”
“So we are the only two people on this entire planet who are not part of this constant organic waveform?” Flier asked, her head tilted back and beak open with incredulity. She laughed a deep, long laugh.
“What’s so funny?” Anti asked.
“Here I am, having served for centuries as head of the Guardians, this grand, self-important, galaxy wide association of highly intelligent species, and after 30 years here, I had not noticed that in the very place where I live, evolution has taken another jump. That the technology that makes the Guardians work is not even needed here. If that’s not funny, I don’t know what is.”
They all laughed. Diver was happy to see Flier peek out from the laconic nest she had lived in since arriving here.
“Yes, sometimes we are just straight lines for that cosmic joker, the universe, eh?” Diver said. “But that’s extraordinary news. What does it mean?”
“A few things,” Mari said. “One, there’s hope that this is not an isolated ability that just Adno’s people have. There’s me, and…”
“There’s me,” Anti said. “When I was little, and Mari just born, I also became part of their waveform through her.”
“Anything else you want to tell us while we’re revealing secrets you’ve kept for decades?” Diver asked, trying not to be annoyed.
“Yes, some other things,” Anti said.
“Well, let’s get it straight from the source,” Mari said.
They felt Adno’s presence.
“I apologize for keeping you in the dark, Diver who is my mentor and Flier who is my hero,” she said. “But I had my reasons. When I brought you here, it was because I had learned that Hanikori had actually assembled a shadow organization within the Guardians, and that they had a plan that was secret from us. I was concerned that they might have developed capabilities like my people that would allow them to mine your knowledge. So I thought it best to protect you from this knowledge.”
“We would never have told them,” Flier said, angry and disappointed that her loyalty would be questioned.
“No, of course not,” Adno said, pausing to consider her next words. “But you might not have known you were being probed.”
“Are you saying they can entangle with us without our knowledge?” Flier asked.
“Maybe. We can. But we rarely do — we consider it immoral under most circumstances.”
“Most circumstances? When would it be moral?” Diver asked.
“When the giant killer endor fish come from the deep for us, we do not ask whether they are hungry. We know their minds and act accordingly.”
“And Hanikori?” Flier asked. “Is he coming from the deep for us?”
“Not for you, just yet, but for the humans,” she answered. “If he can finish them off, he can empty the Guardian’s plate, as you land dwellers like to say, of any duties tending to emergent civilizations. Right now, he hides behind Green, who is of two minds, but one mind is weak and doesn’t stand up to the other. They think I do not know, that I am a silly fish who is too dumb to leave the water. They cannot see that my mind can swim everywhere they can walk or fly. And then some.”
“Where do you see them flying to?” Mari asked, prodding her to tell her parents.
“I have been careful to limit my secret entanglements with them, so I haven’t been able to fully understand that. There are layers. They will tell the Council that Earth is hopeless and that I should be reassigned. But I know that is not the whole truth. They are planning something else, something that Hanikori will use as an example to redirect the Council’s work.”
“Redirect it to what?” Flier asked.
“That is what I do not know. When you were forced to resign, I sensed that he was very pleased that you were compromised over the issue of inducing entanglement in Lina.”
“How did you know about that?” Flier asked. She had never told anyone but Diver about that.
“Let’s just say I was able to eavesdrop on fragments of discussions he had with Green and Putnomo. Please, I would have done the same as you, so I’m not judging you. But I think the reason he is pleased is that by letting it leak that you had done that, he drew attention away from his plans to do much more than that, and with many more humans. While he was hammering away at you over Lina, he himself had already entangled with several humans, posing as another human named Hank. He nearly had Raefe killed — we had to help Lina organize an escape from his home rock to her home rock. But I’ve not been able to track Hank recently.”
Diver began to feel her resentment rising that she had been kept out of the loop for so long, but then felt the anger that rose in Far Flier now. For so long, Far Flier had suppressed her response to the humiliation and defeat that Hanikori had dealt her. Now that he had been unmasked as a total liar and hypocrite, Flier felt no reason to rein in her feelings.
“And Earth? Raefe and Lina? Des and Nyssa? The other, weaker entanglers?” Diver asked. “What will happen to them?”
“We are making plans with Raefe and Lina,” Adno said. “Already, we have been able to make a school of 10,000 humans, thousands of them entangled. And 100 of them acting as a single mind, charting the way forward. We will not abandon them.”
“She means that Raefe and Lina have been part of a large group of refugees,” Des said. “Even as we speak, they are holding a gathering of 10,000 people from around the world to figure out a plan to change their world.”
Diver felt the joy of that. “I am so happy to hear that. And happy for Raefe. I remember that he was nearly mad from the voices he heard before he understood his abilities. I have followed your reports, Adno, for years. And talked to Raefe and Lina now and then. But this is a giant step forward for them. Maybe a new step forward for the humans. This is wonderful news. You have done wonders, Adno.”
“And we’re behind you. Whatever we can do. We won’t let Hank or whatever Hanikori hides behind destroy it,” Flier said. “Hanikori will no longer glide unharried on the currents, free to dive for his prey whenever he wants. In a few years, I will breed as a female. I will birth an army, if it takes that, to stop him.”
Diver smiled. Usually she was the one to call up such ancient images. Flier was calling on inner strengths, and Diver knew she had many. Hanikori would come to regret what he had done to Far Flier, of that Diver was sure.



