            <Title>A new job</Title>
            <Text>A new job
Traveller’s Perch
October 10, 2081
“Do you remember sitting here 30 years ago, when we began our project of reforming the Guardians,” Hanikori asked, waving at the plaza in front of them. It was a cloudy day, no suns visible in the sky. But it was a pleasant temperature, and people were walking about, smiling, talking.
“I do,” Green said, “while we sipped bitter tea. And worried that Far Flier would find out.”
“You were worried about him?”
“Weren’t you? He embodied the Guardians back then.”
“And then he didn’t,” Hanikori reminded him.
“He seems to have removed himself from the Guardian waveform,” Green conceded.” Not just the Council, but the whole organization. It’s been years since I felt his signature in the waveform.”
“Yes, his vaunted dedication seemed to decline rapidly once he lost control of the organization,” Hanikori said. “Just as well. He would only have been a hindrance these past years. Speaking of which, I have some ideas I want to bring up at the next Guardian Council. I wanted to get your reaction first, though.”
“I’m all ears.” Green found Hanikori’s fake inclusiveness tiresome. He would do what he wanted to do, and the rest was pretense.
“It’s time that we transform the Earth project to be one of active stewardship,” said Hanikori, “not passive monitoring. If your department was focused on finding the timelines where we could be most effective, we could also periodically nudge civilizations through occasional gifts of technology and knowledge.”
“You want to remove the ban on active interference from our activities? Do you think the council will go for that?”
“Yes, with your support and Putnomo’s, we’ll have the votes. He’s already on onboard.”
“Well, you know you have my support. But what about the Ambassadors? And Earth?”
Hanikori smiled. “Dear old Earth. The 20 most advanced civilizations in the Galaxy have spent the last 130 years worrying about that odd little lot. Quite remarkable.”
“They’ve felt like that one little child in the nursery who just won’t learn their lessons.”
“Well, you have more experience with children than me, but that seems apt,” Hanikori said with a hint of the distaste that the subject of procreation usually brought to him.
“Do you see just cutting off the whole project?”
“No, no,” Hanikori said. “We owe them something, I feel. We’ve mucked about in their affairs on and off, probably done more harm than good. But we can bring it to a successful conclusion.”
Green was intrigued by Hanikori’s oblique reference to his failures on Earth. “Are they a difficult people, is that it? Did you find them that way?”
“Me? No, not at all,” Hanikori said as if surprised. “I was thinking of the mess Diver made. But I think we have some things in place, and some hidden reserves.”
“Oh?” Always drama with Hanikori, he thought. Just get on with it.
“Well, first there’s Adno, the fish who took Diver’s place.”
Green was slightly taken aback at “fish.” Adno was from a race every bit as intelligent as theirs. “Fish” was what they ate for dinner. “How do you mean?”
“Adno’s people are water dwellers. They exist as schools. Humans live on land, they exist as individuals in very loose and conflicting groups. She is, if you will pardon the pun, out of her depth with them,” Hanikori said, laughing at his own joke.
“Funny,” Green smiled back. “So you’re suggesting that if I leave her alone, the whole thing will eventually just, as it were, fall into the ocean?”
“Undoubtedly,” Hanikori said. “But that is not actually what I was thinking. We should lead by example, don’t you think? If we can bring the Earth project to a quick and successful conclusion, we will silence lingering doubts among the Guardians.”
“And your plan for that is?”
“Contrary to popular belief, I did not spend my time as ambassador to Earth wandering around in ignorance. I admit that the Korean initiative backfired badly. But I put in place initiatives that are just now bearing fruit. For example, one of the most powerful men on Earth now considers it commonplace to converse with a voice in his head named Hank. He’s grown quite fond of Hank, and values his advice highly. Why not — I’ve given him knowledge no one else on Earth has, and it’s made him fabulously rich. Of course, he doesn’t know that Hank is an alien from an advanced civilization 20 light years distant.”
Green stared at him for a moment, absorbing the notion that Hanikori had been secretly involved somehow in Earth for over 100 years. Every time he wanted to trust the man, something like this caused him the deepest of doubts.
“You are troubled,” Hanikori said. “You think it was wrong of me to do this on my own. But I have always been clear that leaders must lead, from wherever they can. This is not about me. I turn this over to you with no reservation.”
“And what is it you want me to do?”
“You will sense in my mind a number of different numbers. You will also sense some other data. The numbers you will recognize as coordinates, but they are encrpyted. If you think of the data and the numbers together, the actual coordinates will resolve. Only you can do that — certain aspects of your brain waves that are unique to you form a private key. Anyway, if you go to that location, you will find all the information you will need to carry on.”
What more secrets does this man hide, thought Green. He would have to find that out. For now, he was very curious about what Hanikori had in mind for Earth.</Text>
