            <Title>White Christmas</Title>
            <Text>White Christmas
Newcastle, Republic of Northern England
December 22, 2081

The Urban Gypsies had the rooftops, the Northern Guard the alleys, while the citizens of Newcastle walked the main streets, unaware that a battle between them might break out any minute. 
“You see the Guards over on the east side of that big building?” asked Gordon Brown, the Gypsies’ leader. He handed Raefe the binoculars. “They’re the real problem. The rest are just wankers, but those guys are hardcore.”
Raefe looked, but he had already felt the harsh glare of violent energy coming from the small groups Gordo was pointing to. How many times in the last 30 years had he witnessed a band of desperate armed people filled with that exact feeling? Some, like the Gypsies around him, gave off a more complex set of emotions: hope that by fighting they could end fighting, longing to wake up without the feeling of threat all around them. 
But many, like these die hards from the Northern Guard, had drunk the cocktail of violence and power that seemed to be the unofficial drink of a society dissolving all around him. It was all too easy to put a gun in someone’s hands and all too easy for armed bands to believe that guns inoculated them from the end of the world as they knew it. 
If only they could all experience the warm ties that bound people together in the Free Alliance. But that’s what he was here for, to bring them into the fold. He turned to the Gypsies that were with him.
“We talked about how to sense people’s emotions. Can any of you feel what’s going on inside their heads?”
“Don’t know as I want to,” said Claire, a compact little woman of about 35. “Bloody scary what’s in their heads.”
Raefe smiled to himself. They were new at this. Blood scary indeed. They couldn’t read the Northern Guards’ thoughts — neither could he. But they could read their feelings. Well, eventually. He remembered the first time he had felt someone else’s feelings. It was supremely odd, yet there was also a sense of familiarity. You thought, oh my, no one else thinks like me. But eventually you found the greater truth: our feelings are unique in the same way as our appearance. No two people look alike, but plenty of people resemble each other. Like one of those police sketch kits — you could make up almost anyone’s face by assembling a handful of bits from a few dozen choices. Feelings were the same way, if a bit more expansive and complex.
He had read a 20th century novel that had a scene where a child draws a picture. This took place before puters, and the girl had to use a piece of paper instead. And she didn’t have a light pen with a color wheel. Apparently back then they gave little children pen-shaped pieces of colored wax. They would come in sets. This little girl had a set with 12 different colors (why did 20th century people have all these ways of counting that had to do with 4 or 6 or 12? Did it have something to do with the calendar?) so she couldn’t draw all the flowers in the garden properly. She wanted the box with 88 colors. With 88 colors she could draw most anything and it would look real.
He had found that most people had about 100 emotions, but even then, they were related in groups. But the difference between any two people was not just which color and how strong each  was, but how one could amplify another, or tamp another down, or, well, even after all these years, he hadn’t really figured it all out. Everything affected everything, that he knew — they were all woven together, more like a tapestry than a drawing. Or maybe more like an electronic circuit, each component affecting the others in nonlinear ways.
Nonetheless, he had become fluent in the nuance of human emotions, and to the extent that the heart and the head were aligned, it helped him greatly to understand what other people were thinking. And so he had been able to understand how his own actions could change other people’s thoughts and feelings, and that had made him more confident in his ability to communicate. And he knew this would happen to all of them, in time. Right now, though, they were doing well to be at the 12-crayon stage.
“I know, that’s our first reaction,” Raefe said. “And maybe it is scary, but unless you start to understand what makes them tick, your choices are to ignore them or kill them. Both have unpleasant consequences.”
“Well, at least killing them is effective,” Irish Liam said. “I could take a couple of them out from here, Gordo, take ‘em right off the board. Wouldn’t that be best?”
“Is it?” Raefe responded sharply, intervening before Gordo made a snap judgment. “Because they have mothers and brothers and children, and they’ll grow up to hate you. Surely, you’ve seen that already.”
“Aye,” Gordo said. “Can’t argue with that. Half of us are here because of what they did to our families in the past. Let’s take a pass, Liam. We’ll get our chance soon enough, I’m sure.”
“The one in the blue shirt,” Claire said. “She’s full of anger, no… more vengence. And deep grief, too. Now and then, a fond remembrance — maybe a lover? No, maybe a relative, images of a boy, maybe a brother. All stewed up together. Very intense, that feeling.”
“You’re wondering what it means,” Raefe said. “Maybe he lost a brother to a rival gang or in one of McDornish’s campaigns. She wants payback. Worth noting that as vague as it seems to you, it’s not much more rational to her. Just a feeling she lives with, all the time.”
A few blocks a way, some gunfire erupted as another group of Gypsies stumbled into a Guard patrol in an alley. Raefe could sense emotions spiking at the sound of gunfire.
“I can feel their fear,” Ganesh said. “Deep fear. So many layers of fear. They’ve been afraid since they were little berns.”
“That’s what I’ve often found,” Raefe said. “People who live in tough places live in fear constantly. It’s not obvious because they mask it by being scary themselves. But it has deep consequences.”
Before he could continue, more gunfire erupted and closer to them. The Gypsies returned fire across the now deserted streets. Raefe lay still on his side behind the low wall at the edge of the roof, hoping the brick would deflect any bullets. After a few minutes, the Guard decided they had had enough and headed back toward their own turf in central Newcastle. Gordo herded them all back to the dark, deserted streets where the Gypsies had their headquarters in an abandoned warehouse. They all collapsed on a bunch of old sofas strewn around in the second floor room that passed for their headquarters.
“I see how the Guard roam the city,” Raefe said. “It’s intimidating most of the people, although obviously not you guys.”
“We can give as well as we get. But right now, we’re up against it,” said Gordo. “When Brian McDornish came on the scene in ‘63, he promised the North a new start and heaven and earth in the bargain. Five years after the split from the South, he’s nowhere near that, but he’s also had time to push his opponents off the stage. That’s let him keep his failures in Northern England pretty quiet. So people still have faith in him.”
“When you say people have faith,” Raefe asked, “what do you think they see to have faith in? Him? His movement? His worldview?”
“Mostly, they fear what he says he fears,” Gordo said. “After this afternoon, though, maybe I’m changing my mind. Maybe they were already afraid, and he tells them what of. Anyway, his support comes mainly from two communities — the old British Anglo-Saxons and the Hindu Nationalists. You know we had the big riots between Hindus and Muslims in ‘74, and McDornish took control during that. Basically, he’s made an alliance between the old Brits and the Hindu Nationalists against the Muslims and the Euros.”
“But not just that,” Claire said. Despite her very black skin, she had a thick Scottish accent. “I came down from Glasgow after ‘74 because of what McDornish said about the corpos. It’s not just blacks who followed him for that, either.”
“It’s true,” Liam said. “All my old mates from the docks are McDornish supporters. More than that — half of them are muscle for him. They think he’s the man who can show those poshies in London that they don’t run the world.”
“And yet, he uses so many of their methods,” Raefe said. “Divide and conquer, intimidate, buy off.”
“That’s where we’re stuck,” said Gordo. “The Urban Gypsies stand for the urban poor who have no permanent homes, no place in the scheme of things. There’s millions in the Newcastle area and tens of millions in all of Northern England who fit that description. But he’s got them more worried about the 30% who are Muslims. It’s easy for him to rant against the Corpos — they’re on the other side of the border. But real action — he’s got the other 30% who are Hindus fighting the Muslims, and the whites cheering them on.”
“It’s rubbish, what he tells the Hindus,” Ganesh said. “Me and my brother Mikey, we were street kids in Little Mumbai in ‘74. McDornish recruited us to be soldiers for him. Filled our heads with all this nonsense about being real Brits. Me and Mikey and our mates — we weren’t even against the Muslims. Played football with ‘em, some of us had Muslim girlfriends. But he made it seem like real Northerners, they wouldn’t stand for them, so get with it.”
“What changed your mind?” Raefe asked.
“Court Street Community Center,” Mikey said. “I mean, the whole thing was daft — like some  kids playing vids after school were a threat to the nation. I watched those white boys cheering while the place burned, those Muslim kids trapped inside. I felt in my heart they would  do the same for some other brown boys like me and Ganesh when it suited them. All that talk of how we could be real Northerners, like we weren’t already. Born and bred, is me and Ganesh.”
Raefe could feel the anger and tension in the room. How many rooms had he sat in like this the last 30 years? The frustration of the dispossessed.
“Well, I think the Urban Gypsies are on the right track.” Raefe said. “You’ve made common cause between all parties. And McDornish can’t deliver — the old ways aren’t going to solve what we’re facing. And you’re about the new ways — the new economics of social profit, human benefit.”
“What you said about fear  — how do we fight that?” Claire asked. “All well and good for people to get jobs that put a few quid in their pocket without destroying the planet. All for it. But what about the hate?”
 “You understand this will take generations, right?” Raefe said. “Look, it’s a piano tune we have to learn to play. The left hand is fighting for what you see — food, housing, the rest. The right hand is what you can feel — we’re not each other’s enemy, we don’t have to all love each other to stop hating each other. It’s a war of inches and years. That’s why I came here — I hope you’ll become part of the Free Alliance.”
“Tell us more about what the Alliance is doing,” Gordo said. “We only get sketchy reports here.”
Raefe gave them his standard rundown. How Citizens of Nowhere came to be. How they joined forces with the New Voodo Army, which was really the start of the Free Alliance. How he had roamed the world since 2050, seeking out like-minded people.
“At this point, we have thousands of small groups like this, all over the world. What we have found is that in the corners of society, away from the money and the Net buzz and whatnot, the old society is dissolving. Often the first result is gangs and terror. But after that burns itself out, people discover that the government and the big corpos don’t give a damn what they do. They see people like you and places like this as a waste of their resources.”
“Happened here, for sure,” Irish Liam said. “No one’s replaced a broken street light in living memory.”
“Exactly,” Raefe said. “But I if you go to Area 7 in Mumbai, you’ll see that the neighborhood now supplies its own streetlighting. The big software companies in Mumbai upgrade their solar panels to the newest tech every few years. Most of the workers at the recycling yards live in Area 7. About 10 years ago, they starting scavenging the panels and created the first solar/battery streetlighting network in the city’s history. People who agree to have a panel on their roof and maintain it get some of the power for free during the day. And then Area 7 went to the tech companies and worked out an agreement whereby the Area 7 teams replace the panels at the tech complexes every five years. In exchange for their labor, they get to keep the old ones. Then, through the Free Alliance, Area 7 gets technical assistance for many other things and contributes their know-how on street lighting. Many other member groups are now following their example.”
“Spiffy,” Irish Liam responded. “But what’s that got to do with us?”
“When the hardcore guys from the Northern Guard, go home, does their neighborhood look like this?”
“Pretty much,” Irish Liam said. “Most of the buildings are only partially habitable, or have no water or juice.”
“Tell me, anyone here have any ideas of what you could do about it?”
“Well, we’ve all got a few,” Gordo said. “But it’s pretty fucking complicated. Before the split with the South, the local corpos were pushing factory built houses that had standard plug ins for power, water, etc. That left out all that was trained to be builders — carpenters, plumbers, bricklayers, etc. But some are still around. They could fix stuff up — if they had supplies and a reason to.”
“C’mon Gordo,” Ganesh said. “You know if we did that, the Guards would bomb the place.”
“And us to them,” Mikey said. “Let’s be honest.”
“And if you could get past that, learn to trust each other?”
“Be a cool day in Hell,” Irish Liam said.
“And that’s the other side of the Free Alliance,” Raefe said. “Combining new economics with a new social attitude — empathy. Starting from what share, not what divides us. I think you all got a taste of that out there today — once you were able to tune in to your enemies’ emotions, you all recognized them. Because you have many of the same feelings. There is no us versus them in the end — it’s only us versus us. We should be able to win that fight, don’t you think?” he said, hoping the little joke would open the door for them to agree. 
“It’s all spiffy, mate” said Claire. “But like in a dream, far off. What do we do tomorrow?”
“Whatever you can to disarm their fear,” Raefe said. “There’s no magic bullet. You must find ways to show most of them that you’re not the enemy they think you are. In time, as you strengthen your empathic abilities, you will learn to connect with them and they will actually be able to see into your hearts. Hopefully, that will be a good experience for them.” 
They all laughed, some a bit more nervously than others.
“At the same time,” he continued, “you can’t just surrender to their threats. Some of them are truly past reasoning with; they’re addicted to violence, and them, you have to oppose. And you can keep reminding them that McDornish can’t deliver. But ultimately, we all have to start to focus on the corpos.” 
“Much as I despise them, they’re not shooting at us. And we can’t avoid buying from them — they make most everything. Except a good brown ale!” Gordo laughed.
“Don’t kid yourselves. The corpos have their claws into McDornish. They push him to suppress the Gypsies. Where do you think he gets all his intelligence from?”
“So you think we need to storm the City down in London?” Claire asked.
“No, they’re too clever for that,” Raefe answered. “They’ve scattered around the globe. I’ve worked for 30 years to make them an endangered species. Urban Gypsies are not alone. Citizens of Nowhere are the most advanced part of the Fee Alliance, and it frightens them  —millions of Africans taking themselves out of the global market, creating an alternative ethical economy, generating our own energy from wind and sun, and so on. And it’s not public yet, but Holland is going to take a huge step — you know about Everywhere?”
They shook their heads.
“Holland is going to become the first virtual nation. Most of their land will be underwater in another 50 years anyway. So they’re offering citizenship to anyone anywhere in their new virtual nation, Everywhere. If you pay their 10% income tax, you’ll be a Citizen of Everywhere. They’ll give you a passport and social benefits and protection of basic human rights. You get a vote for their parliament. While there is room, you can live in Holland, but you don’t have to. They don’t say it, but they hope other  states will merge with Everywhere and increase their ability to absorb people. The corpos are irritated. They thought they could just absorb the old nation states and do away with all of that, but Holland has refused to play.”
“Wow, that could be the start of something for sure. How do you think the corpos will respond?” Gordo asked, looking cautiously interested.
“We’re working on finding out. But I expect that their first play will actually be against traditional governments. They’re weaker every day, and they still have more people than Everywhere.”
“Excuse me,” said a small, dark skinned girl, perhaps Persian. “I hate to interrupt, but I’ve just been monitoring the Northern England military frequencies, and there’s something you need to hear.”
“Go ahead, Ea,” Gordo said. “Raefe, Ea is our best hacker and electronics ace.”
“Thanks, Gordo,” she said, slightly embarassed. “Look, the long and short of it is that the military have gotten reports from Iceland and Norway that the Gulf Stream inversion we always feared has finally happened. For five straight days, the surface temperature in the ocean north of here has been dropping.”
“What’s happened?” Raefe asked.
“Well, they’re not saying,” Ea replied, “but most likely a major piece of ice sheet has fallen off of Greenland. This is what everyone’s feared for years — the fresh water has submerged the water salt water coming up from Africa and South America.”
“What’s the weather report?” Mikey asked.
“That’s why I’m interrupting you,” Ea said. “Iceland weather reports massive storms forming out at sea. Basically, a snow hurricane is headed our way, along with a 10 or more degree drop in temperatures. Early indications suggest more than a meter of snow, possibly much more. We won’t see the sun for weeks.”
For an instant, Raefe felt that awful cold wind blasting his face on Truro Island, the last thing he had ever felt in that timeline. He shuddered, realizing that the time that the Guardians had bought him and Lina was now almost up. In only 30 years, this world had come to the same point as that other Earth. They would not have long to get to some kind of global higher ground.
