            <Title>Close to the edge</Title>
            <Text>Close to the edge
Dadaab
September 21, 2081

Lina looked out across the plain of Dadaab. Ten thousand sets of eyes looked back at her from a sea of faces of every sort. The First Worldwide Congress of the Dispossessed was about to start and you didn’t have to be an empath to feel the high expectations.
“Did you ever expect to see this?” she asked Raefe, squeezing his hand.
“Some days, yes. But not that many,” he acknowledged, smiling. “And the best part is, we don’t know all of these people. There are so many new groups represented here, from so many parts of the world.”
A band played “Wet Feet on Desert Sands,” the song that had become the anthem of fugees everywhere. Voices rose slowly until there were ten thousand people singing as one:

We leave our homes
In the sea
We walk the streets
With wet feet
Our feet water the deserts
That we meet
We are the future
That we greet
Hey, Ho, Forward We Go!
Over the din, the amplified voice of Lina’s old friend Edna could be heard.
“Welcome, delegates to this congress and people of the new world! I am Edna, of the Council of Nowhere.  For so many years, we have wandered in the deserts and marshes, wondering where our homes would be.  After more than 30 years, more than 1 billion people roam the world, each step bringing them to a new home.”
The crowd had hushed now, letting the weight of a billion fugees sink in.
“The old homes, that we had in the old world, are gone,” Edna said. “Many of you never lived in that old world, before the ice melted, before the seas rose, before the rains stopped coming. So you feel the truth of what I am about to say: that we will never have that home in that world again. 
“So what is this new world, and where is our home in it?” she continued. “That is what we are here to discuss, and hopefully, decide. You can see I am an old woman. And I have spent my life almost entirely in the ashes of the old world, as have many of you. Now it is time for us to remember the story of the Phoenix, who rose from the ashes to fly again. Those who have turned this world into ashes, they have lost their right to tell us how to live. It is our time to decide that for ourselves.
“All around the world, new ways have emerged from the disasters of the last 30 years. Here in Africa, the Citizens of Nowhere, who originally arose in East Africa, merged our new model of citizenry with the New Voodoo Army’s new economy in Nigeria in the 2050s. Since then, our ranks have swelled to 70 million people across Africa who have their own economy, their own social institutions, and their own homes in the wastelands deserted by the profiteers, false prophets and thieves who moved on to easier plunder.
“Some of you come from Southeast Asia, where you have had to give up the rice paddies that your ancestors worked for 2,500 years. More than 400 million people from Shanghai to Bangladesh now live only in boats. Almost 50 million of them belong to the Rising Tide, a water-borne equivalent to Citizens of Nowhere. And just as the New Voodo Army changed Nigeria from a toxic chemical dump to a livable place, Rising Tide is changing the way fishing is done, restoring the coastlines and seas of Asia to a sustainable state. And all without the involvement of the corpos who seek to profit from our hardships.
“Change is not just coming from fugees. From Europe and the Americas, we have seen experiments in the concept of social profit and cost. The Urban Gypsies of the Republic of Northern England create viable communities in the poor neighborhoods of that economically ravaged republic. Recently, a much more prosperous piece of what was once known as the Kingdom of the Netherlands became a global republic, accepting citizens wherever they live, no matter they’re history. You pay taxes, they offer to protect your human rights and provide basic social benefits, totally upending centuries of what the nation state has been.
“After decades of plundering the Amazon and fostering toxic urban poverty, the elites of Brazil were forced by mass action to comply with a completely new political economy, neither capitalism nor socialism, but combining aspects of both. Will it work? Time will tell, as it will for the new nations forming in Europe and North America that are neither run by the old elites nor one of the new corporate states. For us here, now, it is yet another example of how we might choose to go.”
She talked for a while longer about how the conference would work, and soon the crowd broke up into discussion groups. Edna stood apart, deep in thought.
“You’ve all done a great job in bringing everyone together,” Raefe’s thoughts found her.
“All in one place, at least,” Edna said. “Now the work of bringing them together begins.”
Raefe wandered through the crowd. For 30 years, he had traveled to meet groups large and small who were desperate for deep and fundamental change. He had listened to their grievances, their hopes for the future. He brought them news of Nowhere and all the other groups popping up in the shadows of the world world, all around the globe. In every place, he had also met others with empathic potential and if they were willing, he had helped them to learn entanglement. With Adno’s help, he had located thousands of potentials and been able to help most over the threshold to be able to use and control their empathic powers. The day was drawing near when their combined power could sustain a global waveform.
Still, few here knew what he looked or sounded like. Outside of Dadaab and the Nigerian village that he and Lina had lived in for awhile, Raefe had carefully avoided the limelight. His skill as an empath had not just enabled him to communicate more deeply with people — it had also shown him how many people feared such closeness. Sometimes their fear could lead to violence. But not here — today he was among friends.
He sat quietly on the edge of a group from North America as they compared their experiences and shared their ideas on a way forward.
“We live on the new coast,” a young woman said. “Our town used to be the hilly section of a big city that was part of the old state of Connecticut. Now there are only a few hundred buildings left standing above water. You can walk down the main street right into Long Island Sound. You can go inland from our town, but not up or down the coast — we’re cut off by bays both north and south.”
Raefe had a fleeting image of East Somerville, water rushing between the stanchions of an elevated highway, before he and Lina had been transferred to this timeline.
“How long have you lived like that?” he asked. He noticed that her shoulders were tattoed with a riot of colorful birds done in smart ink that changed colors in a complex, repeating pattern. It was a design that had been popular about 10 years ago, and the smart ink suggested that she had once lived a very comfortable life.
“For three years,” she said.
“What’s your situation now?”
“Strange,” she replied. “Connecticut no longer exists — most of it was ceded to DigiBrands in exchange for managing a long list of potential disasters. But they don’t want us because we have nothing of value to them. We’re more No One than Nowhere.”
Raefe smiled. “How about Someone Somewhere?”
She laughed. “Some Some, then. I like that. Anyway, there’s a large farmer’s cooperative about 200 kilometers north, along the Connecticut River. With the new weather, that’s actually a very fertile area now. We buy food from them, and smuggle it in to avoid DigiBrand’s taxes. We think in a few years, the sunken town will become like a reef, so we’re investing in fishing gear and shellfish farming supplies. At least we’d be able to feed ourselves.”
“The rest of you, what’s your biggest need?” Raefe asked. “Food, water, shelter, power, or services like education and healthcare? And tell us who you are, please.”
“All of it,” shouted a wiry young man from the back. “I’m Karl, from Pittsburgh, still part of Pennsylvania, still part of what’s left of the United States of America. Which are not united, and not very much of America. Anyway, we should have it good. The rivers are full and we got hydro off of them. We got farmland in every direction, and the warming’s actually improved our growing. But that’s attracted too much attention.”
“How so?” Raefe asked. Karl was an unremarkable young black man, hair cut in the current fashion of thin orange sides, a braided row circling the back of his head, and a paintbrush wedge of curls standing up on top. Raefe noticed a triangle tatto on his neck; it was from some prison in the U.S., he couldn’t recall which.
“We got the New Confederacy in what was West Virginia. They’re hooked up with Billy Warren, who’s basically taken over the old Koch empire. They actually tried to blow up one of our dams to force us back to coal! Warren’s got other friends in Ohio and they try to control the movement of food on the roads. We had good contacts with some farmer’s coops south of Cleveland, but now Warren’s people want us to pay exit fees for the food to leave Ohio. And then there’s some biker gangs roaming through western PA — sometimes they ride into neighborhoods on the edge of Pittsburgh and just take whatever they can. All down the line, we’re dealing with this kind of shit.”
“What’s your plan to fix this?” a middle aged man demanded of Raefe.
“You’re the plan,” Raefe smiled. “This is the plan.” He waved his arm toward all of the other small groups.
“You brought us here just to talk?” the man said, incredulous. “I came for answers. I’m ready to fight, even to die. But not for nothing.”
“You’re Walt, right?” Raefe said. “I’m Raefe.”
“I know who you are,” Walt said.
“When you were a boy, Walt, did you learn about the fall of the Roman Empire in school?” Raefe asked.
“Sure. The barbarians destroyed them. Not so different than us, eh?”
“Just so,” Raefe answered. “You think any one of those Roman emperors that lived in 200 or 300 could have had a plan to stop that? No, because the Roman Empire just couldn’t work anymore. It was too big, too dependent on conquest and slavery. That’s our world — it doesn’t work anymore. It’s too big and too broken for a plan. No one knows what’s next.”
“So what the hell are we doing here?” a   woman in her late 40s yelled out. “I’m Connie. We’re close to the edge out where I’m from. We’ve got people on all sides trying to crush us. We could have people hunting us for food in a generation.”
Raefe could feel her fear. He could tell her that he had spent time with many gangs like the ones she feared, and that cannibalism was not their first option. But he had learned that fear made people blind and deaf. He hoped she could someday learn to read emotions, and she would understand that while she had many things to fear, being eaten was not one of them. Not for many generations.
“We’re doing what we can,” Raefe responded. “I don’t think cannibalism is an immediate threat. But here in Africa, we’ve spent 30 years beating back the kinds of threats you may face soon in North America. You probably already face them on a small scale: Karl’s bikers are like the pirates and raiders that plague Africa. We’ve dealt with human traffickers who scoop young girls by the village full to sell to corpos and gangsters.  Water pirates who seize a dam or pumping station and demand ransom or no water.”
“Well, that’s reassuring,” Connie said, deep with sarcasm. Suddenly, Raefe understood where she was coming from. She had been genetically engineered, probably back in the ‘60s, when it was all the rage among the middle classes. Supposed to make them more competitive with the corpo kids, but the tech just succeeded in unbalancing people. After a long legal battle, the biotech companies behind it had agreed to reverse the effects, but people were still left with odd personalities.
“Look,” Raefe said. “We may not know all of what comes next, but we do know a few things. We need an economy that doesn’t keep driving the temperature up. We need a governance system that doesn’t let people who have a vested interest in the old ways obstruct the new, while we figure that out. And with so many people’s lives shattered, we need a culture that prevents us from fighting over the remnants, as much as possible. And then we cycle back to the economy — it also has to help the fugees. And so on. So what have you tried? What do you want to try? What do you know of what people who aren’t here are doing that’s worth considering?”
“That’s all good, but until then how are we going to keep those NeoCons from killing the 60% of Pittsburgh they consider inferior beings?” Karl asked.
“In the New Voodoo Army, we learned that guns are only a temporary help,” Raefe said. “We’ve learned that you can disarm your opponent, but until you’ve disarmed their fear and the hatred it enables, you haven’t done anything. We’ll spend a whole day on that later in the week.”
“I don’t hear any urgency from you,” Walt said. “What can we do now?”
“I’ll tell you how urgent this is to me,” Raefe said. “I’ve spent thirty years working toward this week. Pretty much every day of that thirty years, too. And I can’t make it all go away for you, even after thirty years. We have to start thinking differently, stop pretending that our problems just need the right magic spell to fix, the right shortcut on our vid game controller. We have to change history. We have to change the way we live. And the way we live with each other. Thirty years is like 30 seconds for that. But we have to start.”
“True ‘nuff,” Karl said. “But start what?”
“Right now, we need people who are willing to try new ways of living. We need people who will commit to new arrangements that don’t make the climate worse, that don’t aggravate racism and ethnic strife, that don’t enforce patriarchy and so on. When they find ways that work, we need them to defend them, yes, but also to continue evolving and refining what they do. And we need  people to commit knowing it may not work, knowing in a few years they may have to start all over, in a completely new way. That nothing is certain and everything is up for grabs. Humanity must travel on a long and dangerous voyage to another planet — sustainable Earth. We need people with that kind of courage and commitment.”
Raefe could sense their excitement, but also continued skepticism, all mixed with the lingering fear that their daily lives now brought. We have to send them home with more than that, he thought, and set off to learn more from the delegates.
</Text>
