            <Text>Just a few enhancements
September 19, 2081
Hanikori reached the back of the cave and found the boulder that stood a meter in front of another passage. Unless you were standing right next to the back of the boulder, you couldn’t see the opening. And from back here, you couldn’t see the front of the cave. So no one would know where he would disappear to, even if they had managed to follow him to the mouth of the cave without him knowing it.
He remembered the day 30 years ago that he had gathered 17 of the Guardians to plan e12 here, the chaotic energy of the lava below a natural shield against prying minds. Amazingly, they had been able to keep their  secret through all of this time. But they still had a long way to go on the immortality project, and he wasn’t going to relax just yet. For the next phase, he had to have access to test subjects on Earth. And he needed Putnomo to do a few things that would enable that.
Using the techniques that Putnomo had shown him those many years ago,  he initiated his own waveform in the secret subchannel that Putnomo had created to link the Wormhole Interface Network and found the scientist on his world 453 lights years distant.
“How goes the work on e12?” Hanikori asked.
“Slowly, I must admit,” Putnomo answered. “We can all be recreated as waveforms in plasma — we’ve mastered that technology. But allowing us to manipulate the material world in that state — we have big obstacles, still.”
“Yes, yes, it’s hard. I get that. But have you made any progress?”
“Yes, in the sense that we’ve ruled out our third approach. We have four more to try — will any of them provide a reliable mechanism? And then we have to engineer a way to do it easily.”
“And a timetable?” Hanikori asked.
“No less than ten years,” Putnomo said. “I wish I had better news.”
“I’m not surprised, given the difficulties so far. All the more reason my next request becomes important.”
“What’s that?”
“I’d like you to develop a package of enhancements for the humans. Life expectancy, 1,000 years. Ability to entangle with other enhanced beings without our help. You can absorb some of the minor details.” He opened his mind to allow Putnomo to scan them.
“You want me to enhance the human race?” Putnomo asked, incredulously.
“Of course not,” Hanikori said. “I want to be able to enhance a handful of humans. Really, only one to start with.”
“And how will you deliver it?”
“You’ll have to give me instructions on building and deploying the enhancements that I can transfer through the waveform to an individual person there. Then they have to be able to find people to make what you describe.”
“Hanikori, you might as well ask me to tell one of the birds that fly above your world how to become you. There are layers and layers of technology that humans have no inkling of that would go into extending their lives for 1,000 years.”
“Damn it, Putnomo, do you always have to draw everything out, complain about how impossible it is? I’ve entrusted you with our science program. Can you deliver? I’ll give you a week to come up with something.”
He waited awhile after breaking off with Putnomo, gathering his thoughts. The scientist always annoyed him with his insistence that everything was hard, that everything would take a long time. They both were in their seventh century yet that made him impatient for change and Putnomo deliberate and tiresome. But he was the key to the e12 immortality project, so Hanikori would just have to put up with him, despite his veiled threat to dismiss him. Let him worry, Hanikori thought, even though he had no intention of letting go of Putnomo. Or of telling him how he would use the enhanced Earther.
Calmer now, he reached into the Wormhole Interface Network and found his subject asleep on Earth. He inserted himself into Billy Warren’s dream, a dull recounting of the prior day’s trip on one of Earth’s incredibly old-fashioned coal-powered trains. In the dream, Warren was sitting in a train car, looking out as the scenery passed by. Hanikori sat down next to him.
“Pretty, isn’t it?”
“Oh, hey, Hank, nice to see you again. Yeah, it’s something ain’t it. See those deer up on that ridge? Those Hot Earthers want to put windmills up there. Scare the damn deer off. Not on my watch!”
Hanikori suspected the deer only roamed the ridge in Warren’s dreams, the woods they roamed in actuality having been ravaged by rising temperatures and forest fires. But it was Warren’s fierceness of purpose and determination that made him attractive, whatever his other flaws. He could deal with Warren’s delusions later.
“Yeah, I know what you mean, Billy. There are a lot of small minds in the world. But I have something that I think could be what you like to call a game changer, Billy. I wanted to run it by you.”
He gave Billy a glimpse of being enhanced. How he would be virtually immortal, how he would be able to read other people’s thoughts at will, and hinted at more to come.
“Wow. Are you saying you can help me become like that, Hank?”
“Just so, Billy.”
“And why would you do that?”
“Because I believe in what you are trying to accomplish. And what you are doing requires time.”
“And what do you want in exchange?”
Hanikori smiled. Warren wasn’t exactly the sentimental type.
“Humanity is nearing its end. The planet can’t support billions more people. And the culture is lost in a mire of what you call egalitarianism, on the one hand, and blind tribal strife on the other. I know you know that not every person is equal, that some can see farther and accomplish more than others. And if humanity is to survive, it must recast itself based on those people. So I want you to start that process, to bring together other people like yourself, and with the knowledge that these gifts will be yours, develop a plan to reform Earth based on the best of you.”
“You’re right that we are mired in those things. Even among the elite, there’s no agreement about the way forward. But I have some ideas about a core group that could potentially accomplish this, especially if we have access to the things you promise.”
“You bring them together, and I’ll deliver,” Hanikori said, and broke the connection. Warren was so full of admiration for himself, but if Warren could deliver on his end, and Putnomo on his, Hanikori could finish the Guardian tradition of passive involvement. Immortality would not eliminate the need to monitor lesser species for impending threats. But this way, they could reliably transform worlds to reduce their threat to future generations. Maybe they’d blow themselves up down the road, but at least the Guardians would always have a backdoor into those worlds to neutralize them as a threat.
And the best part, he thought, was that he had Warren on the hook. When it came time to find subjects to test out Guardian immortality technology, he’d be in no position to say no.</Text>
