            <Title>Fully mindful</Title>
            <Text>Fully mindful
Dadaab
September 22, 2081
Lina smiled to see Nyssa and Des sitting in one of the discussion groups, listening intently. She could feel their passion and their desire to speak, but they had learned long ago to listen first. That was the culture in Nowhere before she had arrived, and it had never wavered in the 30 years since.
“You must be proud,” she heard Fatima’s thoughts as the woman walked up behind and put her hands on shoulders. “Your children, now grown, now leaders.”
“Amazing, isn’t it,” she thought. “When Raefe came here in 2051, I had no thought of being a mother. I felt like I was already raising a child — myself. But the more time I spent with him, the idea grew on me. And then to have twins! But they are as much children of Nowhere as of Raefe and me. You and your mother and so many others taught them your way.”
“Our way,” Fatima corrected. “You forget how much we in Nowhere look up to you. I know you think of yourself as African, in some way, but when you came, you were the Chinese girl to everyone. And I mean everyone. The girl who walked away from power and domination to join us. And then her American boyfriend arrived and did the same. It was a powerful statement.”
Lina smiled to see Nyssa and Des sitting in one of the discussion groups, listening intently. She could feel their passion and their desire to speak, but they had learned long ago to listen first. That was the culture in Nowhere before she had arrived, and it had never wavered in the 30 years since.
“You must be proud,” she heard Fatima’s thoughts as the woman walked up behind and put her hands on shoulders. “Your children, now grown, now leaders.”
“Amazing, isn’t it,” she thought. “When Raefe came here in 2051, I had no thought of being a mother. I felt like I was already raising a child — myself. But the more time I spent with him, the idea grew on me. And then to have twins! But they are as much children of Nowhere as of Raefe and me. You and your mother and so many others taught them your way.”
“Our way,” Fatima corrected. “You forget how much we in Nowhere look up to you. I know you think of yourself as African, in some way, but when you came, you were the Chinese girl to everyone. And I mean everyone. The girl who walked away from power and domination to join us. And then her American boyfriend arrived and did the same. It was a powerful statement.”
“Maybe, but Raefe and I were no more than on the outskirts of our own worlds. Whatever privilege we had felt heavy and cumbersome, like a winter jacket on a summer day. A jacket we had borrowed to play dress up in. And our empathic abilities were far more interesting and alluring than the pull of our home worlds, if you know what I mean. Since then, Nowhere has absorbed millions of people who are only part African or not at all, for that matter. Your mother and Alton were much more key to that than me or Raefe.”
“Well, it’s a good thing we are all friends, then, eh?” Fatima laughed out loud and continued on, speaking out loud now. “Do you think we are close to trying our grand new experiment?”
“Let’s see what the organizing committee thinks.”
Lina reached out to the 10 people who were running the Congress. 
“Everyone,” she started. “How is the discussion going? Are we ready for our next phase?”
The discussions were going well, many ideas had come forth. Maybe not too many more would be, as there was a sense that they had reached that point where people were starting to repeat themselves. They all agreed that after three days, it was time to move to a consensus. Edna walked to the stage at the front.
“Friends,” she said. “Let’s take a break from our discussions. For three days, we have gone deeply into the problems we and the world face. Everyone has spoken, many ideas have been put on the table. But what we all want to know is, what can we do next? And we have a very innovative idea of how to figure that out. To explain, I want to ask Raefe Epstein-Miller to come up.”
Raefe had mostly stayed out of the limelight for the three days. He was surprised as he walked toward the stage by the loud cheers and clapping. By the time he got to the mic, all 10,000 people were standing and singing “Wet Feet.” Standing at the mic, looking out, he paused to try and understand what they were feeling.
“Thank you, thank you. I share your hopes, I agree with you that we are on the verge of something big and new and full of life. I accept your warmth and your thanks, and I can only say that I will do what I can to help us all fulfill the promise that we all carry with us. About 100,000 years ago, there were just about as many people here in Africa as there are here at this Congress today. Science tells us that they were far more interested in collaborating and learning from each other, in sharing their discoveries and in trading their secrets and their possessions, than they were in fighting over territory or mates. In their way, they understood that only together would they survive. It is incredible to me that for decades, powerful people who want us to believe that they are smarter than us have argued the opposite view.
“Those ancient people weren’t perfect. They did sometimes fight and even kill each other. But they seem to have never lost sight of their commonality. They never dismissed each other because of different customs or outlooks. In fact, they were hungry to meld their own rough sketch of life with other’s equally incomplete ideas. And that’s where we find ourselves here on Day 3 of the First Worldwide Congress of the Dispossessed, with various groups of people having worked out some thoughts, some partial plans. How do we move forward?
“When we planned this event, the 10-member committee that all of you elected to represent us debated this point longer than any other. One night, I had just come from one of these meetings and was sitting on a bench near my home, staring into space, trying to grapple with the challenge. A young man from my village stopped and we talked. Most of you know that many of the Citizens of Nowhere have learned to be empaths, to sense other’s thoughts, and to let them sense theirs. This young man is an empath and he asked me why we wouldn’t use that ability to create a platform that crystallized the true sense of the group. Often, in public gatherings and groups, the loudest or the smartest or simply the most persistent win the day. Maybe people who are none of those things have a better idea but no one has heard it. At that moment, I knew he was on to something.
“After much thought, we have come up with a process to move the discussion forward. We have ensured that every discussion group has contained a good number of empaths who have trained and developed their talent. They, in turn, have done what they can to understand those with less developed empathic abilities. And now, this group of about 100 empaths will meet for a few hours and share their thoughts with each other. For the first time in human history, we believe, a group large enough and diverse enough to capture the vast majority of thoughts and emotions will connect in a way that’s deep enough to actually reveal those thoughts and feelings in their fullness to each other.
“But first, I want to say what we, the organizing committee, have asked them to do. We have not asked them to come up with a list of tasks you can do or demands that you can take back home and fight for. No, that will not get us far. What we are trying to accomplish, what we need to accomplish, will take generations. And at the same time, we need to win improvements now, to alleviate suffering now, to halt further decline now.
“So we will be coming up with a set of principals and tests that can be applied to any proposed action or change. We will learn as we go which of these are more important than the others, but we will have a start. Are you ready to begin?”
The crowd left no doubt that they were. Raefe let their energy wash over him but he also probed further, trying to find the roots of their mood. They were optimistic, buoyed by their days together, hopeful. The Congress would be a success. But the next hours would determine whether it would be an historic occasion, though, or just an important one.</Text>
