        <Document ID="156">
            <Title>Power failure</Title>
            <Text>Power failure
Dadaab
February 3, 2082
Once Manfred had shown them the files, they set to work analyzing them. They were vast and difficult. Des created a way for Adno’s school to absorb them, and soon thousands of minds were at work, each linked  to the other in a way that made it easy to connect the dots. Des stayed with the school most of the time, fascinated to learn their techniques. Now he was taking a break.
“So you do this 24/7?” Nyssa asked him. “Are you aware of it?”
“Yes and no,” he said. “Sometimes, it’s a bit like having a day dream, or like when you drive a car and are thinking about something completely different while driving. It’s hard to describe. More and more, I’m not that aware of it until I find something interesting.”
“Remember Mrs. Odipo?”
“Our third grade teacher?”
“Yes! She was so boring, droning on forever. But of course, I had to listen because every once and awhile, she would say something that I knew would be on the test. So I would listen to her in the background and then perk up when I could sense from her that this was something she would put on the test.”
“Yes, that’s a bit of how it is,” Des said. “And this time, there is a really big test.” He shared what he had found with her.
“We have to tell everyone,” she said, quite alarmed. “This cannot happen.”
*****
“We now have the big picture,” Nyssa said to her family and their friends on Water Eye. “And I think you guys on Water Eye were right to suspect Hanikori. The magnitude and insanity of this plan is way beyond Warren or the other corpos, so we think Hanikori must be involved.
“Warren’s convinced most of the world’s leading oligarchs to construct an underground society of the elite. Being literally underground, they could wait out the continued chaos and destruction that would occur around the world as the climate continues to change and more and more people become homeless and loose any source of food.”
“How big a community?” Raefe asked.
“They had been talking 100 million, then 10 million,” Nyssa continued. “Now they talk about 1 million. The best sense we can make out of it is that they are having trouble recruiting.”
“And that takes us to the second aspect of this,” Des said. “We think they are promising people that if they join, they will live for a thousand years and have all sorts of powers.”
“He’s promising to give them the enhancements that we all have,” Flier said. “Genetic remodeling, nanobio maintenance, organic computing elements, the works. This is madness. In our long history, no Guardian has ever broken that barrier.”
“But there’s more, outside of the docs Manfred gave us.” Des said. “As you know, I’ve learned how to access networks with my mind. For weeks, I’ve been slowly meandering through the inner nets of UFS, which took me to DigiBrands, which took me to Warren’s own nets. And I’ve discovered something.”
“Wait, you were able to do all of that through your empathic ability?” Lina asked.
“I can’t explain it,” Des said. “It’s not about empathy, since we’re talking computers here. But I think it is about entanglement. And I think maybe because our nets are always so full of emotion — all the chats and entertainment and all of the stuff that’s not really factual that’s on the nets — that I somehow was able to cross that line. The truth is, organically, our abilities are based on quantum interactions, not human-level concerns.”
“You may be the first person in the Galaxy who can do this,” Raefe said.
“Unfortunately, that’s not true,” Des said. “Mari and Anti have told us that Hantikori is conducting secret research on transforming his species and others into a kind of living computer. And, I’m not convinced that Warren himself is not some kind of trained empath. He has had contact with Hantikori, after all.”
“True, we can’t rule that out,” Raefe said. “So tell us what you have found.”
“You should be receiving the full data,” Des said, “but the short of it is that Warren’s cabal is planning on sabotaging the nets world wide. Their goal is to accelerate chaos here on the surface.”
“Why?” asked Lina. “We seem to be doing that all on our own.”
“In part,” Des answered, “because he’s a bit of a sociopath. But their group is not doing so well attracting recruits to the new world order. So they want to shock them into joining through fear. They’ve created a super computer virus that will bring down electric power grids world-wide. They’re also selectively targetting banks outside their own, some governments, military nets and a bunch of other targets.”
“What do they think will happen?” Lina asked.
“They’ve done sophisticated modeling of the impacts,” Des said. “The short version: what’s left of the world economy will disappear. The only corpo-level businesses that will still function will be theirs. No governments or military large enough to matter will be able to respond. People around the world will be living in a world that no longer can buy and sell food, clothing or water from more than a few klicks away and only by bartering. More than 2 billion people will lose their jobs within a month. And the entire world will be in the dark, not knowing exactly what happened or why.”
“And here’s the worst part,” Nyssa said.
“Yes, I was getting to that,” Des said. “They will leak out small dibs and dabs that suggest that it was Everywhere that did this. They’re still deciding whether to go further and say it was empaths who did it.”
“I’ve been waiting for that,” Raefe said. “All these years, somehow we’ve been able to live without being a secret but without having a spotlight.”
“We’re not ready for this,” Lina said. “We’re still a year or two from Everywhere having the numbers and organization to take on something like this. Although, I’m not even sure I know how we would do that.”
“We think we know how,” Nyssa said. “Thanks to Adno.”
“Adno’s people are all entirely entangled with each other all the time, without the interface networks the Guardians us,” Des said. “Yes, they live as a school, so that makes sense. But that doesn’t mean other empaths can’t do that.”
“We felt something like that at the Congress,” Lina said. “And Edna’s people have been exploring that for years.”
“And now Anti and Mari have learned it from Adno’s people, and we have learned I from them,” Nyssa said. “And now we can teach it to thousands, millions on Earth.”
</Text>
