            <Title>A rude awakening</Title>
            <Text>A rude awakening
Cambridge, MA,  on another Earth
November 7, 2048
It was Saturday and Raefe was, for once, not going to bother checking in with work. The Titan Towers sim could wait until tomorrow. His MiniWorlds pay had just been deposited,  he was full up on credits, young, healthy, and ready to have some fun. 
The wall Vid said no rain, high 62 — a typical early November day. He clicked his Voice on.
“Manny, Raefe. Are you around?”
A second later, Manny clicked in.
“What’s up Raefe?”
“Got a chip full of credits, a nice day, and no work. What’s up with you?”
“The same. Me and Raquel are going to the club tonight, but I’m free until then. You’re welcome to come later, too, if you want.”
“I’ll probably pass on that. I thought maybe things were going to get in motion with someone at work, but turns out she’s in more a girl phase right now. I’m checking the Club’s meetup wall  on my puter and I don’t see anyone that interests me. I don’t think I can bring myself to work the floor cold down there tonight. So, no thanks.”
“I hear you. We could get some sweats in. You want to meet up on the Harbor Trail?”
“Cool. Say 10?”
“Yeah, Castle Island at 10.”
He clicked the call off and got his stuff together for the bike ride down to Castle Island. Hopping on his bike, he avoided looking left at the MinWorlds building next store. He didn’t even want to see it today. Monday he’d go back to being a grunt. Today was his.
He tooled out from his apartment through the small condos and ethnic restaurants of TechTown and into ritzier North Point. He knew a little shortcut path that wasn’t on any maps that cut out the security checkpoints all around the edge of North Point — you never knew how long they would take. Pleased that he had once again avoided that inconvenience, he merged back onto the main trail that took him over the bridge into Boston. 
A few minutes later, he was pedaling at full speed, feeling the ocean breeze as it started to filter into the city. He loved this little stretch of trail. It was usually pretty empty and he could ride fast, the wind in his face. And then up a little hill and down and there was the whole harbor, out in front of him. 
He barely remembered the view before the trail had been built. In ‘31, the long-predicted rising seas had finally hit Boston, temporarily flooding everything along the waterfront. In typical fashion, the city had none nothing about it, despite a number of lesser repeats. But in the aftermath of the economic crash six years later, some smart person had made sure that all property on the waterfront — now an economic disaster of its own — was bought up, leveled and turned into a sort of levee to protect against future storms. 
The crest of the levee was a flat, winding strip about 50 meters wide, with a bike trail running down the center. The weekend crowds hadn’t come out yet and the trail was almost empty. The sun was bright enough that he avoided looking off to his left, but he came up and over a ridge that turned him toward the harbor and the sun exploded into his view. He winced, wondering why his sunglasses weren’t doing a better job as the sun grew brighter. It hurt now, his head throbbed, he gasped, blinded now. Without thinking, he let the wheel hit the grass that bordered the trail and fell over, but the bright light somehow still pierced his eyes, like a laser trying to drill through the back of his skull. The light became more discrete, like marbles inside his head. They pulsed in a complex rhythm that never seemed to repeat. He could barely notice or think of anything else.
After a few minutes, the process began to reverse itself, becoming less intense. Lying on his side, not sure where he was or what the hell was going on, he was frightened. Where was the water? Was it going to wash him away? What was he thinking? He was on a ridge looking down to the water, many meters above it and half a kilometer from the shore. But he was filled with dread that the water was going to wash him away.
It’s going to be OK, calm down, he thought. You’ve just fallen on your bike. You must have gotten some dust in your eye or something.
Where did that huge wave go? some part of him asked and he realized that he could hear another set of thoughts that seemed to be from another part of his mind. Something was wrong with his brain, he thought, he had to get help. He must be having a stroke or some kind of attack caused by a tumor.
No, it’s OK, the other voice said. There’s nothing wrong, just give it a minute.
And he sat dumbfounded as some part of him he had never known slowly explained that some other version of himself had come from other version of reality and was now rattling around inside his head, trying to tell him it was going to be OK. Was he going insane? It didn’t feel like that. This other self was very familiar, comfortable almost, like a very old friend that he had somehow lost touch with but was now instantly familiar. Without thinking much about it, he could feel a rapid fire exchange of images and words going on. It was enticing, as if he was looking into a mirror and saw himself, only he was slightly different, and the guy in the mirror was explaining how different and there was nothing really odd about that, was there? After all, there were an infinite number of universes, he had read that somewhere, hadn’t he, and this guy was from one of them, and it was a very similar universe, but he had to leave it because he was going to die in a huge tidal wave because of climate change and some aliens had helped him and now he was going to be here in his head but they would merge soon and it would all feel perfectly natural. If only he could just remember how to move his limbs and get up off of the ground and back on his bike.
Oh, sorry, the voice said. You should be OK now.
And he felt his body again. The sun was just the sun again, even if it looked funny and sideways. Oh, I’m lying on my side, he thought, wondering how long he had been there.
“Are you OK?”
He looked around and saw a young woman straddling her bike.
“I saw you riding in front of me and then all of a sudden you went down like a bag of groceries, like you had been shot,” she said. She had a wrist Voice and her hand was poised to activate it. 
Suddenly, he felt her anxiety and an image popped into his mind of a black-haired young man lying on the ground, his techie bike clothes odd for someone with his disheveled hair and barcode tatto on his neck. He looked slightly wild-eyed, something pained in his expression. Raefe realized he was seeing himself as she did. How did that happen? 
“Oh, thanks for stopping,” he said, trying to keep the panic out of his voice. “I’m OK. I was just daydreaming, I guess, and I must have caught the edge of the grass with my front wheel and just gone down. No damage, as far as I can tell, other than my pride.”
“OK, just wanted to make sure you weren’t hurt,” she said and then was gone, pedaling off fiercely.
He tapped his ear and asked his Voice what time it was, confirming that it had all happened in an instant. I think it would be best if we just continued with the day, his other self said, and just let things take their course.
“Sure,’ he said, realizing that he had spoken out loud. “Sure, if you say so. Have you done this before?”
“No, this is new territory for me, too,” the voice said. “But Mars Girl gave me a sense of what it would be like and so far, this is pretty normal. If you can call transferring your consciousness to another version of yourself in another timeline normal. Mars Girl — Diver is actually her real name — has much more experience with this than me, so I took some comfort from her advice.”
“Who’s Diver?” he replied, wondering about the Mars Girl part.
“Oy, we’ve got a lot of catching up to do,” his other self said to him.</Text>
