            <Title>Changing the rules</Title>
            <Synopsis>Raefe and the team run the new game, with it's empathy algorithms. </Synopsis>
            <Text>Changing the rules
Cambridge
July 12, 2049
Raefe sat in the back of the small auditorium, watching images flow into and out of the big vid screen upfront. This was what he had come back from Dadaab for — his part of the grand plan, a sandbox to build a new world in. For the visitors, it was the same, only the world they would build with it would be quite different.
His reworked code had allowed the team to fulfill their grant. Enough quantum storage cubes to build a small house with were full of the data his code had generated would keep the RI people busy for years. For the few millions they had spent at the Toot, they would be able to propose wringing billions of dollars of social benefits out of the system with a more informed hope that it wouldn’t spark riots or unintentionally bring the wheels of commerce to a grinding halt. Meanwhile, everyone oohed and aahed as the Civilization Project slides traced their incomplete history of humanity. “Wait until version 2!” was the mantra. All it lacked was a catchy theme song.
When it was done, the RIers went off amid prodigious mutual backslapping to celebrate the completion of the project. Roshi stayed behind.
“When you’re done cleaning up,” she said, “come see me. We have some things to discuss.”
Ah, the work is done and now I’m going to be packed off back to MiniWorlds,” he thought. Not that he hadn’t expected it, just not so soon. He got the room in reasonable shape. No use killing himself on it if he was going to be gone any way. He walked down the hall to Roshi’s office thinking he would miss this place.
Roshi feigned busyness as he walked in, as if she had something on her puter to finish first. He had learned to recognize her little power games over the months. Harmless amusement.
“Well, that went well,” she said.
“Yes, I’m glad. It was a very interesting project to work on.”
She didn’t respond for an extra beat or two. He suddenly was aware that she was unhappy, or angry.
“I’m sure you understand that with the project coming to an end, we’ll have to wrap up your role here.”
“I sort of figured that out. I mean, Elise and Joe alluded to some future iterations and so on. And it would be fun. Is that not in the cards?”
“Elise and Joe are no longer connected with the Civilization Project,” she said. She projected calm, but he detected a cold anger.
“Wow, that’s some news,” he said, buying time as he tried to process what was going on.  “What happened?”
“Look, I’m going to give you the benefit of the doubt here,” she said. “I know all about their alternate sim, with your empathy codes and all that. I’m going to assume that was their doing. I’ve had my doubts about Elise all along — there were some sketchy things in her past in Brazil. But I can’t have team members secretly undermining our grants.”
“What are you saying about what she did?” he asked, trying to sound uninformed and naive.
“Let’s just say that the code she had you write could potentially be used not just to simulate our society, but to simulate how our society could be overthrown. I believe Elise is secretly working for some kind of underground revolutionary group in Brazil.”
“Wow, she never said anything about that.”
“Yes, well, she underestimated both me and the Reagan Institute people. We have our own resources and that’s all I’m going to say about it. But I won’t say anything to MiniWorlds. I don’t think you had anything to do with it, and it wouldn’t be fair to you.”
He could tell she was lying. Words would be said, he would be under a cloud at MiniWorlds. How bad, he couldn’t tell. Was she lying about Elise, too? He found it hard to believe that he had never sensed any duplicity from Elise. And what about Joe — was he also unaware of Elise’s supposed other agenda? Roshi hadn’t said anything about him. Maybe he should reach out to Joe and sound him out.
The more he thought about it, the more anxious he became. He knew how hard it was to use anything on the Net without drawing attention. His Voice, his puter messages, the vids he watched — all that had been routinely scanned since the Slide by the government. In the aftermath, many governments had suggested that the Slide was the work of terrorists. By the time the truth came out that it was a botched weapons test by the U.S. government, many countries had already built elaborate autoscanning systems and few decommissioned them. He’d met people who claimed that they knew holes in them and ways around them, but he couldn’t trust that. He had to assume they were full of it, or deliberately trying to lure people into fake safe zones.
He took the subway to the end of the line and hailed a ride with his Voice. He gave the driver an address a few blocks from the last library in the western suburbs. He walked to it and sat down at a puter. Most of the other patrons were old and poor; they came here because they were homeless or couldn’t pay Net fees. Like them, he pulled up local news, read a few stories, and intermittently, started a search for Joe. He got lucky. 
Joe was involved with an AI group that had RoboSmart games. These were like the old-fashioned quiz shows that still lived in online vids — old shows like College Bowl and Jeopardy had cult followings. College students got together and watched them, trying to beat the contestants without looking every question up online. Joe’s group hosted events where three robots competed to answer the same kinds of questions. The results were sometimes hilarious, as the robots didn’t always correctly parse the kinds of questions an average school kid could understand. But they were getting smarter as programmers like Joe learned from their silly mistakes.
This weekend, there was just such an event in Boston. He’d go, and hope Joe was also there. He had to figure this out quick, before events got the better of him.

 
</Text>
