            <Title>Bootstrapping</Title>
            <Text>Bootstrapping
Cambridge
July 20, 2049
He felt Lina tickling his mind.
“Raefe, the most wonderful thing has happened.”
“Glad someone’s having a good time.”
“Your sim is not going well?”
“You know it. And I’m just stuck. I’d love some good news — what’s up with you?”
“Remember Alton?”
“Sure.”
“Well, after you left, he and the Citizens did reach an agreement of sorts. The Citizens have a high council of sorts, although it’s pretty informal. They were very worried about allying with an army, as I predicted. Anyway, they decided to try a small joint project. So last September, 100 people from each group went off together, on their own, and built a small village. The test was to see if their economic system and our social system could work together and be something more than either.”
“What is their economic system? He started to tell us but I never got what he meant by it.”
“It’s about combining healing the environment with providing food and shelter. In Nigeria, the planted thousands, maybe millions, of mangrove trees to filter the chemical pollutants from the waters around Lagos. Big oil and chemical refineries had made them unusable.”
“Cool, but not that original,” he said. 
“But here’s where it gets innovative. They harvest the parts of the mangroves that actually absorb the pollutants. The plants grow back, and it actually helps them live longer to be pruned like that. They’ve developed simple processes — crushing, burning, that sort of thing — to separate the pollutants from the plant. They purify them through a variety of simple flotation filters, and they’re left with a menu of stuff. Heavy metals, sulfur, phosphorous, organics. Some they use internally to make construction materials. Others they barter to get stuff they need.”
“Cool and original — even better. They interact with global capitalism, but they are really outside the system of debt and currency. And they were doing that sort of thing with the Citizens?”
“Yes, just different pollution problems. It was working well. Fatima was one of the people, and last week, Edna asked me to visit and see how she was doing. Something amazing happened.”
“What? You’re killing me with suspense here.”
“Fatima’s cousin Addisu  tried in his way, to entangle with the other people, but he’s too new at it. But when I arrived, he asked me to help and something completely unexpected happened. Addisu couldn’t sense how close everyone was, but I felt it immediately. I tried reaching out to some individuals who seemed to have the strongest signals, but they were all strong. Raefe, we did it — we created the waveform that Diver talks about. All of a sudden, we could all sense each other, all 201 of us.”
“Holy shit. What was it like?”
“Was? Is! It is fantastic. Let me bring you into it!”
“How?”
“Just relax. You feel that?”
And just like that, as if he was looking out his window at 200 people in a park, he could feel each of their minds. It was a warm feeling, what his grandmother used to call a group hug. But it was complex and shaded. He could get lost in it.
“Yes, there’s so much to explore,” Lina said. “This is how life could be, so rich.”
“I wish I was there,” he said.
“But you are,” she answered. “You are here, just not in the old way.”
He didn’t know what to think. Just then he felt Alton’s mind.
“We meet again,” Alton said.
“I never imagined it would be like this,” Raefe said.
“Yet you seem unhappy,” Alton said.
“No, I’m very happy. But when Lina connected, I was very frustrated. I’ve been trying to understand what you all are doing on a bigger scale, working out how we can understand how this will change things.”
“Lina told me about your project,” Alton said. “It sounds super cool. Can we help?”
“Maybe,” Raefe said. “Things have taken an odd turn, though.”
He filled Lina and Alton in on what had happened with Elise and Roshi.
“So I don’t know what’s going on, and it’s good we’re communicating this way, because honestly, I’m in over my head here. The Reagan Institute, Roshi, these people are in another league. I want to try and find Joe Nguyen, see what I can learn from him. Fortunately, I kept a copy of the code, but it’s not complete and I have no hardware it can run on. If I put it in the cloud, they’ll find it if they want to look hard enough.”
“You should come here,” Lina said. “I think you’re in danger there.”
“You might be right,” he said. “But I think this code could help us and I need to find out what happened. I think Joe’s cool.”
“But you don’t know, right?” she said.
“No, but I have to find out.”
“Let NVA help. They have contacts in America. They can track him down over time. If he’s cool, he’ll still be there. If he’s some kind of government dude or corpo, he’ll have moved on to another situation. We need you.”
“I’m telling you, I sat with those two for weeks and I never felt anything wrong from either of them. I trust them. And I need to know what we’re up against.”
“What if there was someone like you,” Alton asked, “but he was not a good person? Worked for the highest bidder, or worse yet, was a true believer in the corpo way?”
“Have you ever met someone like that?”
“No, but we’re not all that common, us empaths.”
“I’m going to err on the side of trust and track him down.”
He could feel their sadness and frustration with him.
“OK, but we’re going to make arrangements for you to get here quickly if you have to,” Lina said. “We want to err on the side of trust, too, but I think maybe we know how slim that margin of error is better than you. And how disastrous the consequences could be.”
It was his turn to be angry and frustrated that they couldn’t see what he saw.
“Wow, empathy doesn’t solve everything, eh?” Raefe thought, almost exactly at the same instant Lina did.

</Text>
