            <Title>A new school of thought</Title>
            <Text>A new school of thought
Water Eye
July 20, 2049
The waters were cold today. Somewhere, a deep river had begun to wind its way toward the surface, bringing with it trillions of tiny creatures that lived off of material shed by the redfish that lived above, in the warmer waters. Now those redfish would feast on the tiny creatures, growing and shedding old cells that would then feed more tiny creatures in the deep. Larger creatures would prey on the enlarged redfish schools, and Adno’s school would feed on them. Adno could feel the deep contentment of the whole school, their place in this cycle firm and known.
“Many thanks to all of you for helping me with the humans,” she broadcast. She felt their pleasure that the project had been successful.
“It has been many years since I touched the minds of land dwellers,” Arman said. “So many odd sensations. Like being tickled on the belly by a school of little gold speckled min. Quite amusing.”
“Ancient one, so happy to please,” Adno responded. “Did we feel the deepness of it, too? When Lina and Fatima and Alton and their friends connected through us, did we feel the life-changing joy of it?”
The school hummed with pleasant memories. Mixed in, rude jokes began to emerge about that old fart, Tanoch, who had doubted Adno. Did he not understand that she had their strength behind her, that these birds and beasts who lived in ones and twos on the land could sing melodies, but not the symphonies that swelled their waters?
“No, he doesn’t understand. And I’m not ready to let him know. The land dwellers don’t know how to combine so many melodies in a harmonious way. They won’t  understand how we can join as TheManyLargeLoudBlueSchool and still each be free as our own minds. They can only conceive that someone or something forces us to chorus. They have not travelled from birth in our great schools, wandering the vast currents together, taking turns looking for danger, steering, exploring. They are enhanced now, each of them their own school of sensors when it comes to senses. So they will never swim this current with us.”
“Will you tell Tanoch about the humans?” Smi asked. “At least he should know your successes.”
“Later,” she said. “Right now I must learn more about why he has put us in charge of the humans and pushed Diver out. Something wrong is going on.”
“How can we help?” Smi replied. “Diver is one of our favorite land dwellers.”
She explained how she would be able to access the archives of the wormhole interface and get access to the last ten years of data. With the thousands of minds in the school, they would be able to find any suspicious activities within a couple of days of paying attention to it in the back of their minds.
“Your timing is good,” Asmo replied. “The skies will be dark these next nights. We will relax, leave our hunting until the moon returns. We can mine your data easily.”
Later, she swam to the wormhole interface that had been modified for underwater use and installed on Water Eye long ago. But Adno had learned to do something her ancestors had not even thought of. Just as she was able to entangle with many others in the TheManyLargeLoudSchool, she could entangle as multiple threads through the interface. She created hundreds of connections, making short work of copying the archives. Even as she felt it enter her mind, she flowed streams of it to her schoolmates.
It was Smi who found the evidence.
“Before you were even an egg, Tanoch was an ambassador to the Yunx. Do you know of them?” he asked.
“No, not really. They became extinct, right?” Adno replied.
“Yes, Tanoch could not divert them from their own destruction. But he also had a secret about the Yunx and Hanikori discovered it.”
“A secret? What could that be?” she asked.
“It is like squid ink in the water now. But he was unusually active in entangling with a certain Yunx, MunzKizzFron, in the days before the Yunx blew themselves into oblivion.”
“MunzKizzFron?” Tra piped up. “I have records of MunzFizzFron being transferred to a new timeline at least seven times.”
“What about other empaths on Yunx? Were there any other transfers?” Adno wondered.
“No one more than once, just MunzKizzFron,” Tra said.
No one else in the school had any data to contradict that.
“Ah, I think I know what happened,” Adno said. “You all see it now, don’t you?”
The school murmured in a low giggle. Poor Tanoch!
She waited for a few days, letting her mind plot the course through these new waters. On the third night of the new moon, she found Tanoch through the wormhole interface.
“Tanoch, I swim the waters looking for the guidance you have left for me, but I cannot find it.”
“Guidance? What are you on about?”
“The currents bring news of big changes in the Council. How is a lone swimmer such as myself to know which currents to join?”
“The Council is none of your business. I’ve told you before. Just keep an eye on Raefe and Lina.”
“I have, Tanoch. It is possible that Raefe is in danger again.”
“Really? Even after we had transferred him to this new timeline?”
“Yes, maybe. Certain other humans may be plotting to kill him.”
“Oh, what crazy theory are you on to now, Adno? Who would want to kill him?”
“People who understand his potential.”
“What humans understand that, besides his partner? What’s her name?”
“Lina. No, not her. And I said ‘people,’ not ‘humans.’ That enlarges the pool.”
“What are you suggesting? That a Guardian is involved?”
“No, but could it be someone from one of our worlds, but not a Guardian?”
“Ridiculous!”
“All the same, can you ask Timelines for advice, as a backup measure?”
“Not a chance! We can’t be shuttling him from timeline to timeline every few months.”
“Oh, forgive me then. Rookie mistake. I thought perhaps Raefe might be in the same sort of jam as MuzzKizzFron.”
Even through the wormhole, she could feel a surge of fear and embarrassment from Tanoch. She counted to three before he began to answer her.
“Muzz? Why do you mention him?”
“As your mentee, I study your work. I noticed that you had him transferred seven times during your work with Yunx. I assumed he was a critical player in their world, much as Raefe is on Earth.”
“Muzz is nothing you need concern yourself with.”
Half the school was listening in, amplifying his emotions, filtering out noise. At that resolution, she could see a complex of emotions trying to hide from her. Ah, now it was clear — her suspicions had been correct.
“No, you are right. Your love life is really not my business. But I am still confused about Guardian policy. If it is possible for you to transfer your lover seven times, why is it not possible for me to transfer Raefe twice in the interests of helping Earth? And do I have to learn how to use the Timeline interface myself, or is there someone who helped you who will help me?”
His fear was strong now.
“What do you want?”
“I want to know why you took my mentor, Diver, off of her assignment to monitor Earth and put me, only a trainee, in charge. I had thought perhaps you would become my mentor, but you give me no help. All in all, I am tempted to believe you want me to fail, and therefore, you want Raefe and Lina and the rest to fail. Is that true? Or shall I make a special appeal to the Council to discuss this openly?”
“I don’t think that will be as helpful as you think.”
“You think I am a stupid fish who doesn’t understand what happens on land. But I have found my way across great oceans, and I will find my way through this, too. Just tell me what you know.”
“Alright, alright. But you don’t bring it to the Council — agreed? That would work out badly, trust me.”
“I can accept that for now.”
“Certain people on the Council want your project to fail. They pressured me to put you on it. My misadventures of the heart with Munzz gave them leverage to insist.”
“But maybe they have other ways to help Earth fail, no? After all, even without me or the Guardians, Raefe and Lina might succeed.”
“They don’t tell me, but I fear you are right. I’ve picked up some whispers that might mean that they will harm them. Or at least him.”
“Whispers? What exactly did these whispers say and who was whispering?”
“I can’t tell you who. But I’ll tell you what, and then you must leave this subject. This conversation itself is dangerous. Perhaps these same people have found ways to listen to our waveform without us knowing.”
Adno had asked Tra to monitor the waveform for ghosts. He signalled here that he had found nothing.
“I think we are safe for now — I have taken precautions. So what is it you may have heard?”
“Raefe could be killed any day now. I’m not positive, but there’s always been that possibility, and I think it may be in motion now. And you should thank me for allowing you to return to Water Eye.”
“Thank you Tanoch. Your secret is safe with me. You should think about how you want to redeem yourself after a thousand years of service. You have made mistakes, but are you willing to work to overcome them?”
She felt him snarl.
“Well, give it some thought. Can I trust that our conversation will remain between us?”
“Yes, yes, don’t worry. I’m not eager to show that my students’ students are now more clever than me.”
He broke the waveform abruptly, leaving her swimming in tight circles, amped up and eager to strike back before it was too late.
</Text>
