            <Title>What you doing with that gun in your hand?</Title>
            <Text>What you doing with that gun in your hand?
Boston
August 6, 2049
Adno felt Raefe’s anxiety as he approached the RoboSmart match. She had promised Lina she would monitor the situation. Lina’s new friends, the New Voodo Army, also had contacts in Boston, and they had promised to show up. Adno had never entangled with them, just Alton, so she wasn’t sure if they were there yet.
She had learned that she could feel other empaths through Raefe, even if he wasn’t aware of them. She quieted her own mind, fully immersed in his. Around the edges, she could feel little spikes of emotion that he was receiving, but nothing significant so far. As he entered the club where the match was, she felt more noise. Ah but there was another mind, very close to him actually. She tried entangling with it and connected surprisingly easily. This one was no novice.
He thought she was someone else, another empath. She withdrew quickly, not wanting to reveal herself. Through Raefe, she could feel the empath connect to his friend, a woman. Jamal and Shawna were there names. Adno opened another thread to Alton, who confirmed that those were his people. All seemed well, then, and she started to relax and refocus on Raefe when she felt a jolt.
Raefe had seen Joe Nguyen across the room and was trying to catch his eye. But even Raefe could tell that Joe was himself entangled with someone. How could that be?  Raefe had never revealed that about himself to Joe, had never felt any such skills in him. Raefe was on high alert now, sensing that Joe was entangled with someone named Hank. Something about that sent chills up her spine.
She opened another thread with her school and asked them all to investigate who Hank was. Something told her it would be better if minds other than hers, minds not known to the Guardians, probed the situation. She turned her attention back to Raefe.
*****
“Hey, didn’t expect to see you here!” Joe said.
“Well, you’re a hard man to find,” Raefe said. “What happened after the big RI meet? I tried to find you and Elise, and poof, you were both gone.”
“Yeah, that was a cluster fuck,” Joe said, looking uneasy. “You heard about Elise?”
“Roshi told me some stuff. Felt like not the whole story. What’s your take on it?”
“She used us, man. She had her own agenda.”
“What agenda?”
“I don’t know the whole story, and honestly, I don’t want to know. But she messed up near the end, I caught her copying all the code to some dead drop server in Brazil. She had all kind of reasons, but it was all bullshit.”
“Why would she do that?”
“I think she’s part of some anarchist group down there. They thought they could use this code to find weak spots in Brazilian society. Put pressure right on the fault lines and boom, there’s a big fissure opening up.”
“So why’d you pull out, too?”
“Honestly, she scared me. Started talking about armed this and armed that. I didn’t want to become a casualty of some guerilla campaign in Brazil.”
“You really think that was possible?”
“Hell yeah. You didn’t hear her. Some of that earnest, nicey Elise stuff — that was just a cover.”
Raefe let that sink in. Someone had been lying. And he had missed it. Elise? Joe? Someone else?
*****
“You’re going to want to feel this,” Tra said. “Join with us.”
Adno merged with Tra’s waveform. Instantly, she recognized a signature in the waveform he was secretly entangled with. It was Hanikori! And he was entangled with Joe Nguyen.
“Hey, Joe,” Hanikori said. “It’s Hank.”
“Dude, what’s up,” Joe replied. “I’m a little busy right now.”
“I can feel that you are with someone. Rafe Epstein-Miller, right?”
“Bingo. Can I connect later?”
“No, this will only take a minute. Keep engaged with him, keep nodding your head and making eye contact while he’s talking.”
“No problem.”
“Remember what we discussed about him?”
“Sure.”
“I think we’re at that point. He can’t leave here knowing what happened. Honestly, he really can’t leave here at all.”
Adno was stunned. Hanikori had established contact before with Joe Nguyen? They had discussed Raefe? What in the three suns and three planets was he up to?
“We’ve probed Joe’s memories lightly,” Tra said. “He and the one who calls himself Hank have been in contact for months.”
Joe was talking to Raefe again.
“Yeah, I can’t really help you on the code, man. She took it.”
“I really need that code. Do you know anyone who could put me in touch with her?”
Joe paused. Adno could feel him considering how to play this. It was an opportunity, Joe could see that. For what?
“Well, I found her one day talking to some sketchy characters outside the lab. When they left, one of them said they’d see her at the Dark Side of the Moon.”
“That’s a real place?” Raefe said. “I always thought that was a joke, the infamous hacker club, like something from a vid.”
“No, it’s real alright.”
“Can you tell me where it is?”
“I can, but you’d never get in. You have to know someone. I could get you in the door, though, and point out these dudes.”
Adno was stunned. She could feel under Joe’s conversation that he was thinking about where he’d stashed a gun, and where he could use it to kill Raefe on this supposed trip. He was in danger, right now.
“That’s cool. When could we go?”
“Can you meet me in the alley behind the club in 15? I’ve got to tie up a few loose ends, and then I’m free.”
Adno was shocked. Raefe had sensed none of this. Hanikori had obviously trained Joe well in evading entanglement. The head of the Guardian Council, with his own private operatives on Earth. How many of these did he have? She would have to investigate this in the future. For now, she had to help Raefe. She reached out to his mind.
“Adno, how nice to feel you. How can I help.”
“I have something to tell you and you must trust me. You have very little time and your life is in danger. Do you see a tall dark-skinned man standing with a short  lighter skinned woman in a corner to your left?”
“Yeah…What’s this about?”
“Joe is not your friend. He’s gone to fetch a gun that he hid in the men’s room. Those two people are Jamal and Shawna. They know who you are. Just tell them ‘Get me out of here, now.’ They’ll help. I have to go now — I’ll be in touch later.”
She let Tra see what he needed to do. She followed Raefe’s thoughts as he met Jamal and Shawna. Thankfully, they didn’t argue and whisked him out the door. Only seconds later, Joe came out of the men’s room and started toward the back door. He stopped, as if he was listening for something. Then he shrugged and turned around and walked out the front door. He got on a solar bike and left.
“It worked,” Tra said. “I was able to impersonate Hank enough to convince him that I’d changed my mind and he should just leave. He’s not experienced enough at entangling to see through it.”
She surfaced, arching upwards out of the water, exploding with all of her might as she leapt high above the water, then plunging back down, down, down until it was dark. She let the currents carry her, trying to calm herself. The only person she could think of who might understand this was Diver. She would have to risk reaching out to her.
*****
Raefe lay low in the back of the van, his face pressed against the back seat. Behind him, racks of baked bread hid the back door. If anyone opened it, they would have to remove the racks to find him. They had been driving to New York for hours. He wasn’t sure what the right thing to do was, but instinctively, he had decided to disentangle from everyone, to withdraw into his own mind, and not connect with anyone, even through speech. He was invisible back here, on the floor of the van, and he wanted to stay that way. Maybe Alton had been right — maybe there were bad empaths at work here.
He rolled over and over in his mind the thought that someone wanted to kill him. Someone thought his little science project was that important? No, that couldn’t be it. Someone thought his mind was that important. Because he was an empath? Or because he was an empath and had been a fugee in another life?
That felt closer to the truth. Someone knew that Lina had been right, that fugees were the future. And they didn’t want empaths meddling in that. They must know about Nowhere, and the NVA, and all of their clumsy attempts to bring people together. They must think that he and Lina would get it right eventually and that they would make things uncomfortable for someone. But who?
He’d figure that out, eventually. But for now, he would take the passport that Shawna had given him, and get on the plane to Lagos, where Alton’s people would find him, and bring him to Lina. They had half-joked that sometimes empathy wasn’t everything. And now he knew which half of that joke was true: a lone empath was vulnerable. Empathy would only carry the day if it was embraced by huge numbers of people. People who had each other’s backs, who could move bigger rocks out of the way than one person, who could extend their eyes and ears everywhere they needed to be.
In a context like that, a piece of software from the geniuses at MIT might be helpful. But it would never be a substitute for that loom of connection, that whole that would be greater than the sum of its parts that humanity needed to become.
He would become a Citizen of Nowhere and trust his fellow citizens to help find that way. No more pretending that he could work within the corpo world, a little off to the side, but part of the machinery. If he was in the machine, he could be crushed. Lina had seen the truth, that the old world was a death trap. From now on, he would travel on the margins, meeting the ones who no one cared about, seeing what they were doing to survive, what new ideas they had. He would help them build a new world, out on the edges, a world where people no longer thought only about themselves, but existed in a web of purpose and connection, of freedom to explore and probe and experiment. As the center shrunk with each catastrophe, the edges would pinch in, until they were strong enough to occupy the center. It would take years, but what choice did they have?


</Text>
