            <Title>Throw the switch</Title>
            <Text>Throw the switch
Traveller’s Perch
March 7, 2082

Green had been dreading this day for months. Hanikori had manipulated him time and time again, pushing him to this moment when he had become a crucial player in ‘Kori’s insane plan to destroy Earth. Green admired Hanikori’s brilliance and his plan for immortality was impressive. Some days, he even thought it was a good idea. The other days, he thought it would never happen but that they would learn many valuable lessons along the way.
But none of that prepared him to help slaughter 10 billion people. Nor to doom a million survivors to the fate of microbes in a lab dish. He had anguished over the whole prospect for a long time. What struck him was that Hanikori had, in fact, never questioned his willingness to do this on a moral level. Why bother? ‘Kori had come to believe he was a god, or maybe even God. His desires were automatically moral, his victims just unhappy accidents. Green knew he was ambitious and sometimes vain, but he would not be a supporting character in this madness.
Of course, he couldn’t tell Hanikori that. He thought long and hard about how to finesse this. And now he had a way.
His part was crucial to the destruction of Earth’s power grid. It was a vast, anarchic system, or more accurately, thousands, maybe millions of systems, each with it’s own idiosyncrasies. Many systems interfaced with several others, they with still others, and so on. Each interface was unique. There was simply no way Warren’s forces could predict the outcome of their actions.
When Hanikori had given Green those secret files last year, they were the specs for all of the power grid controls on Earth. His job was to use the quantum computing power that he oversaw at Timelines to create the most efficient shutdown plan. How fast could he turn out all the lights on Earth, if you wanted to boil it down? And then to use the wormhole interface network to transmit the instructions to Warren’s crew.
He knew that Putnomo had endured endless pressures from Hanikori as well. After some elaborate dance steps between them, they finally had a frank conversation. Putnomo confessed his role in adapting Guardian technology to the humans and transmitting manufacturing and installation instructions to Rosenberg. He was quite doubtful that the humans would succeed. He had tried to tell Hanikori that but he wouldn’t listen. It was like giving a child blueprints for fusion reactor and expecting them to build a working model.
Putnomo might be a laughable figure sometimes, putting on airs, but his people were born to physics. And so it was Putnomo who saw that Timelines were the way out.
“He wants you to transmit a vast amount of information,” he had explained to Green. “That will take a vast amount of energy. Energy and time are related, just as matter and energy are related. If the energy source undergoes selective phase shifts, the transmissions will all go to the same place, but not to the same timelines.”
Green really didn’t grasp it, but the upshot was that it would look like the transmission was going well, but certain bits would go to random other timelines, where there would be no one to receive them or understand or act on them. Putnomo would adjust the central power source to make these phase shifts in response to certain bits of code to render the message unusable in the exact best way. Afterwards, no one would know what had happened, other than that the transmissions would be useless. Green could say he had done his part, and no amount of investigating would uncover what had happened.
None of the Guardians cared about Earth anymore except Hanikori. Green hoped he wouldn’t make a big scene about it. That would only call attention to Hanikori’s misdeeds. Even though the Council were mostly his handpicked crew, Hanikori couldn’t be sure they would countenance such an act of barbarism. Calling Earth a threat was not believable. Green would take the chance.
And he was about to take another chance.
He found Adno’s signature and connected to her through the Wormhole Interface Network.
“How are you, Adno,” he said. “It’s been awhile.”
“You miss me, boss,” she said. “Can’t get along without me?”
“Something like that,” he said. “Listen, some things have come up back here on Traveller’s Perch that I thought we could chat about. But they’re personal, and maybe it would be best to have a more private conversation.”
“Well, that would be easy if I were there or you were here,” she said. “But I don’t know what you have in mind.”
“I have in mind that you know other ways,” he said. “Let’s just say that over the years, certain things have happened that could only be explained that way. It doesn’t bother me, so I never mentioned it. To each his own, and all that. But this would be a good time to let me in on it.”
She cut the connection. Was she spooked? Or making preparations? Only seconds later, he felt her signature, and like that, they were connected outside the network.
“Ok, what’s the big secret?” she asked.
“Hanikori hasn’t just decommissioned the Earth project,” Green said. “He’s got his own plans for Earth, and quite frankly, they’re insane. I don’t expect you to do anything about them — that’s my problem — but I want you to know. Candidly, I want a witness should this ever come to light. Are you willing?”
“Depends.”
“On what?”
“Well, I know that he has recruited some people on Earth to create a private colony of their most elite citizens to live underground. And that he’s given them promises of long life and advanced powers in exchange for that. And that he wants to provoke conflicts that could well lead to the extermination of the rest of humanity. So what do you have to add to that to atone for your participation?”
Green was stunned. “How do you know all of that?”
“You think I am a stupid fish that swims all day on a silly watery planet with only a few smart birds like yourself to look after us. My people have entangled for their entire existence. They can entangle in the millions. They can combine their powers in many ways. We use these powers to help life and I used them to help Earth when that was my role.”
“Earth will need my help, as well,” Green said. “Hanikori asked me to prepare instructions for the humans that will allow them to destroy their power grid in a matter of minutes, never to work again. I can prevent that.”
“Then you should. And I will be your witness.”
“Thank you.”
“And what will you do to stop Hanikori from destroying the Guardians?”
“Why do ask that? What is it you think he is going to do?”
“He wants all the Guardian people to become immortal, to become pure energy.”
“You think that is a false goal?”
“I am immortal already. Born into my school, I have the memories of all who went before. And those after me, they will have my memories. I live a very rich life. But I also get to feel the cools of the water, the lights of the planets, the beauty of my mate partners. Why would I give that up to be lightning in a bottle?”
“Your school will die off someday.”
“And so will the universe. Frankly, it will get bored first.”
“You have your own view, but the rest of us don’t live in schools.”
“You already live in a school, just one that is not self-aware. Your school could evolve these forms of thought and being in time. You could help. We could teach. Your choice.”
Green was confused. He had thought she would be a good, simple-minded witness. Now she was asserting that she was a higher life form.
“You’ve given me much to think about. For now, I just want you to know this. I hope you will not share our conversation with people who would take it the wrong way. The consequences could be dramatic for me. And I wish you and the humans luck. Just remember that I did what I could.”
“My school will remember this forever. Your secret is safe with us.”</Text>
